'''ኢትዮጵያ''' (ብ[[ኣምሓረኛ ፊደል|ኣምሓርኛ]], ''Ityopp'ya'')(ሕጋዊ ስም: ናይ ኢትዮጵያ ፈደራላዊ ዴሞክራሳዊ ሪፖብሊክ) ናይ [[:en:Landlocked_country|ባህሪ በሪ ዘይብላ]]  ናይ [[ኣፍሪቃ]] ሃገር እያ። ኢትዮጵያ ብ[[ኤርትራ]]፣ ብ[[ጂቡቲ]]ን፣ ብ[[ሶማሊያ]]ን ፣ ብ[[ኬንያ]]ን፣ ብ[[ደቡብ ሱዳን]]ን፣ ብ[[ሱዳን]]ን ትዳወብ። ኣስታት 150.350.020 ህዝቢ ይቅመጥዋ። [[ርእሲ ከተማ]] ናይ ኢትዮጵያ [[ኣዲስ ኣበባ]] ትበሃል። 


Some of the oldest skeletal evidence for [[:en:Homo_sapiens|anatomically modern humans]] has been found in Ethiopia.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1038/news050214-10|title=Ethiopia is top choice for cradle of ''Homo sapiens''|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|date=16 February 2005|last=Hopkin|first=Michael}}</ref> It is widely considered as the region from which modern humans [[:en:Recent_African_origin_of_modern_humans|first set out]] for the [[:en:Middle_East|Middle East]] and places beyond.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Li|last9=Feldman|pmid=18292342|doi=10.1126/science.1153717|year=2008|pages=1100–04|issue=5866|volume=319|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|title=Worldwide Human Relationships Inferred from Genome-Wide Patterns of Variation|first11=R.M.|last11=Myers|first10=L.L.|last10=Cavalli-Sforza|first9=M.|first8=G.S.|first1=J.Z.|last8=Barsh|first7=H.M.|last7=Cann|first6=S.|last6=Ramachandran|first5=A.M.|last5=Casto|first4=A.M.|last4=Southwick|first3=H.|last3=Tang|first2=D.M.|last2=Absher|bibcode=2008Sci...319.1100L}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awJVkvnk8KjM|title=Humans Moved From Africa Across Globe, DNA Study Says|publisher=[[Bloomberg News]]|date=21 February 2008|accessdate=16 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629125652/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=awJVkvnk8KjM|archivedate=29 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kaplan|first=Karen|work=Los Angeles Times|url=http://www.startribune.com/world/15860017.html|title=Around the world from Addis Ababa|publisher=[[Star Tribune]]|date=21 February 2008|accessdate=16 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603122801/http://www.startribune.com/world/15860017.html|archivedate=3 June 2013}}</ref> According to linguists, the first [[:en:Afroasiatic_languages|Afroasiatic]]-speaking populations settled in the Horn region during the ensuing [[:en:Neolithic|Neolithic]] era.<ref name="Zarins">{{cite journal|last=Zarins|first=Juris|year=1990|title=Early Pastoral Nomadism and the Settlement of Lower Mesopotamia|journal=Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research|jstor=1357309|doi=10.2307/1357309|volume=280|issue=280|pages=31–65}}</ref> Tracing its roots to the 2nd millennium BCE, Ethiopia's governmental system was a [[:en:Monarchy|monarchy]] for most of its [[:en:History_of_Ethiopia|history]]. Oral literature tells that the monarchy was founded by the [[:en:Solomonic_dynasty|Solomonic dynasty]] of the [[:en:Queen_of_Sheba|Queen of Sheba]], under its first king, [[:en:Menelik_I|Menelik I]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/travel/destinations/africa/ethiopia/mysterious-queen-sheba-legend-church-archaeology/?cmpid=org=ngp::mc=social::src=twitter::cmp=editorial::add=tw20190213travel-resurfsheba::rid=&sf207660858=1|title=In search of the real Queen of Sheba|date=3 December 2018}}</ref> In the first centuries, the [[:en:Kingdom_of_Aksum|Kingdom of Aksum]] maintained a unified civilization in the region,<ref>''Ancient India, A History Textbook'' for Class XI, Ram Sharan Sharma, National Council of Educational Research and Training, India</ref><ref name="Munro-Hay57">[[Ethiopia#Munro-Hay|Munro-Hay]], p. 57</ref><ref name="Paul B. Henze 2005">Henze, Paul B. (2005) ''Layers of Time: A History of Ethiopia'', {{ISBN|1-85065-522-7}}.</ref><ref>Smaller nations that have claimed a prior official adoption of Christianity include [[Osroene]], the [[Silures]], [[San Marino]], [[Armenia]] and [[Caucasian Albania]]. See [[Timeline of official adoptions of Christianity]]</ref> followed by the [[:en:Ethiopian_Empire|Ethiopian Empire]] c. 1137.

During the late–19th-century [[:en:Scramble_for_Africa|Scramble for Africa]], Ethiopia and [[:en:Liberia|Liberia]] were the only two nations that preserved their [[:en:Sovereignty|sovereignty]] from long-term [[:en:Colonialism|colonisation]] by a [[:en:Analysis_of_Western_European_colonialism_and_colonization|European colonial power]], and many newly-independent nations on the continent subsequently adopted [[:en:Flag_of_Ethiopia|its flag]] colours. However, the country was later [[:en:Second_Italo-Ethiopian_War|occupied by Italy]] in 1936 and became [[:en:Italian_Ethiopia|Italian Ethiopia]] (part of [[:en:Italian_East_Africa|Italian East Africa]]), until it was liberated during [[:en:World_War_II|World War II]]. During the Italian rule, the government abolished [[:en:Slavery_in_Ethiopia|slavery]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Goitom|first1=Hanibal|title=Abolition of Slavery in Ethiopia|url=https://blogs.loc.gov/law/2012/02/abolition-of-slavery-in-ethiopia/|website=Library of Congress}}</ref> a practice that existed in the country for centuries, and urbanization steadily increased.<ref name="Accessed 15 May 2008">Shivley, K. "Addis Ababa, Ethiopia" [http://www.macalester.edu/courses/geog61/kshively/index.html Macalester.edu]. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref> Ethiopia was also the first independent African member of the 20th-century [[:en:League_of_Nations|League of Nations]] and the [[:en:United_Nations|United Nations]].<ref>[http://www.thereporterethiopia.com/index.php/opinion/commentary/item/460-ethiopia-and-the-oau-recalling-the-contributions-of-ethiopia%E2%80%99s-pan-africanist-leaders "The Reporter – English Edition"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029210521/http://www.thereporterethiopia.com/index.php/opinion/commentary/item/460-ethiopia-and-the-oau-recalling-the-contributions-of-ethiopia%E2%80%99s-pan-africanist-leaders|date=29 October 2013}}. ''thereporterethiopia.com''.</ref> In 1974, the [[:en:Emperor_of_Ethiopia|Ethiopian monarchy]] under [[:en:Haile_Selassie|Haile Selassie]] was overthrown by the [[:en:Derg|Derg]], a communist military government backed by the [[:en:Soviet_Union|Soviet Union]]. In 1987, the Derg established the [[:en:People's_Democratic_Republic_of_Ethiopia|People's Democratic Republic of Ethiopia]], but it was overthrown in 1991 by the [[:en:Ethiopian_People's_Revolutionary_Democratic_Front|Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front]], which has been the ruling political coalition since.

Ethiopia and [[:en:Eritrea|Eritrea]] use the ancient [[:en:Ge'ez_script|Ge'ez script]], which is one of the oldest alphabets still in use in the world.<ref name="Wilfpag">{{cite book|last=Page|first=Willie F.|title=Encyclopedia of African history and culture: African kingdoms (500 to 1500), Volume 2|year=2001|publisher=Facts on File|isbn=978-0-8160-4472-6|page=230|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gK1aAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> They follow the [[:en:Ethiopian_calendar|Ethiopian calendar]], which is approximately seven years and three months behind the [[:en:Gregorian_calendar|Gregorian calendar]]. A majority of the population adheres to [[:en:Christianity|Christianity]] (mainly the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] and [[:en:P'ent'ay|P'ent'ay]]), and the historical Kingdom of Aksum was one of the first states to officially adopt the religion, whereas around a third follows [[:en:Islam|Islam]] (primarily [[:en:Sunni_Islam|Sunni]]). The country is the site of the Islamic [[:en:Migration_to_Abyssinia|Migration to Abyssinia]] and the oldest Muslim settlement in Africa, at [[:en:Negash|Negash]]. A substantial population of Ethiopian [[:en:Jews|Jews]], known as [[:en:Bete_Israel|Bete Israel]], also resided in Ethiopia until the 1980s.<ref>Weil, Shalva (2008) "Jews in Ethiopia", pp. 467–75 in ''Encyclopaedia of the Jewish Diaspora'', Vol. 2. M.A. Erlich (ed.). Santa Barbara, USA: ABC CLIO.</ref><ref>Weil, Shalva (2011) "Ethiopian Jews", pp. 165–66 in ''Cambridge Dictionary of Judaism and Jewish Culture''. Judith Baskin (ed.). New York: Cambridge University Press.</ref> Ethiopia is a [[:en:Languages_of_Ethiopia|multilingual nation]], with around 80 ethnolinguistic groups, the four largest of which are the [[:en:Oromo_people|Oromo]], [[:en:Amhara_people|Amhara]], [[:en:Somalis|Somali]] and [[:en:Tigrayans|Tigrayans]]. Most people in the country speak [[:en:Afroasiatic_languages|Afroasiatic languages]] of the [[:en:Cushitic_languages|Cushitic]] or [[:en:Semitic_languages|Semitic]] branches. Additionally, [[:en:Omotic_languages|Omotic languages]] are spoken by ethnic minority groups inhabiting the southern regions. [[:en:Nilo-Saharan_languages|Nilo-Saharan languages]] are also spoken by the nation's [[:en:Nilotic_peoples|Nilotic]] ethnic minorities. [[:en:Oromo_language|Oromo]] is the most populous language by native speakers, while [[:en:Amharic|Amharic]] is the most populous by number of total speakers and serves as the working language in the federal government. [[:en:Ge'ez|Ge'ez]] remains important as a [[:en:Liturgical_language|liturgical language]] for both the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] and the [[:en:Eritrean_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Eritrean Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] and for the Beta Israel.

The nation is a land of natural contrasts, with its vast fertile west, its forests and its numerous rivers, and the world's hottest settlement of [[:en:Dallol,_Ethiopia|Dallol]] in its north. The [[:en:Ethiopian_Highlands|Ethiopian Highlands]] are the largest continuous mountain ranges in Africa, and the [[:en:Sof_Omar_Caves|Sof Omar Caves]] contains the largest cave on the continent. Ethiopia also has the second-largest number of [[:en:List_of_World_Heritage_Sites_in_Africa|UNESCO World Heritage Sites]] in Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/&search=&searchSites=&search_by_country=&search_yearinscribed=&themes=&criteria_restrication=&media=&description=&order=region|title=UN World Heritage Sites by Region}}</ref> Additionally, the [[:en:Sovereign_state|sovereign state]] is a founding member of the UN, the [[:en:Group_of_24|Group of 24]] (G-24), the [[:en:Non-Aligned_Movement|Non-Aligned Movement]], the [[:en:Group_of_77|G77]] and the [[:en:Organisation_of_African_Unity|Organisation of African Unity]]. Its capital city, Addis Ababa, serves as the headquarters of the [[:en:African_Union|African Union]], the [[:en:Pan_African_Chamber_of_Commerce_and_Industry|Pan African Chamber of Commerce and Industry]], the [[:en:United_Nations_Economic_Commission_for_Africa|United Nations Economic Commission for Africa]], the [[:en:African_Standby_Force|African Standby Force]] and many of the global NGOs focused on Africa. In the 1970s and 1980s, Ethiopia experienced [[:en:Ethiopian_Civil_War|civil conflicts]] and [[:en:Red_Terror_(Ethiopia)|communist purges]], which hindered its [[:en:Economy_of_Ethiopia|economy]]. The country has since recovered and {{As of|2010||df=|lc=y}} has the largest economy (by GDP) in [[:en:East_Africa|East Africa]], as well as having the largest population in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nazret.com/blog/index.php/2010/02/06/ethiopia_surpasses_kenya_to_become_east_|title=Ethiopia surpasses Kenya to become East Africa's Biggest Economy|publisher=Nazret.com|date=6 February 2010|accessdate=2 June 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2011/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?pr.x=52&pr.y=2&sy=2008&ey=2011&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=644&s=NGDPD%2CNGDPDPC%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC%2CLP&grp=0&a= Ethiopia GDP purchasing power 2010: 86 billion]. [[International Monetary Fund]] (14 September 2006). Retrieved on 3 March 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2011/01/weodata/weorept.aspx?sy=2008&ey=2011&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=664&s=NGDPD%2CNGDPDPC%2CPPPGDP%2CPPPPC%2CLP&grp=0&a=&pr.x=69&pr.y=14 Kenya GDP purchasing power 2010: 66 Billion]. [[International Monetary Fund]] (14 September 2006). Retrieved on 3 March 2012.</ref> Despite these improvements, it remains one of the world's poorest countries.<ref name=":32">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/poverty/publication/ethiopia-poverty-assessment|title=Ethiopia Poverty Assessment|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=2018-12-17}}</ref> In addition to [[:en:Poverty_in_Ethiopia|poverty]], Ethiopia faces hunger, corruption, weak infrastructure, and poor respect for [[:en:Human_rights_in_Ethiopia|human rights]] and access to health and education (with an illiteracy rate of 51%),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.africaw.com/major-problems-facing-ethiopia-today|title=Major problems facing Ethiopia today|website=www.africaw.com}}</ref> ranking in the [[:en:List_of_countries_by_Human_Development_Index#Low_human_development|worst quartile]] on the [[:en:Human_Development_Index|Human Development Index]].

== Etymology ==
The [[:en:Greek_language|Greek]] name [[:en:Aethiopia|Αἰθιοπία]] (from {{lang|grc|Αἰθίοψ}}, ''Aithiops'', "an Ethiopian") is a compound word, derived from the two Greek words, from {{lang|grc|αἴθω}} + {{lang|grc|ὤψ}} (''aitho'' "I burn" + ''ops'' "face"). According to the Perseus Digital Library, the designation properly translates as ''Burnt-face'' in noun form and ''red-brown'' in adjectival form.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3D%232329&redirect=true|contribution=Aithiops|first1=Henry George|last1=Liddell|first2=Robert|last2=Scott|title=A Greek-English Lexicon|publisher=Perseus|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> The historian [[:en:Herodotus|Herodotus]] used the appellation to denote those parts of Africa South of the [[:en:Sahara|Sahara]] that were then known within the [[:en:Ecumene|Ecumene]] (inhabitable world).<ref name="Herodotus1">For all references to Ethiopia in Herodotus, see: [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/nebrowser?query=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126&id=tgn%2C7000489 this list] at the [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu Perseus project].</ref> However, the Greek formation may be a [[:en:Folk_etymology|folk etymology]] for the [[:en:Egyptian_language|Ancient Egyptian]] term ''athtiu-abu'', which means 'robbers of hearts'.<ref>Partridge, Eric. Origins: A Short Etymological Dictionary of the English Language, 4th ed. 1966, p. 188.</ref> This Greek name was borrowed into [[:en:Amharic_language|Amharic]] as ኢትዮጵያ, ''ʾĪtyōṗṗyā''.

In [[:en:Ancient_Greece|Greco]]-[[:en:Roman_Empire|Roman]] epigraphs, ''Aethiopia'' was a specific toponym for ancient [[:en:Nubia|Nubia]].<ref name="Hatke">{{cite book|last1=Hatke|first1=George|title=Aksum and Nubia: Warfare, Commerce, and Political Fictions in Ancient Northeast Africa|date=2013|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=978-0-8147-6066-6|pages=52–53|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=PA4UCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA52}}</ref> At least as early as c. 850,<ref>[[Etymologicum Genuinum]] s.v. Αἰθιοπία; see also [[Aethiopia]]</ref> the name ''Aethiopia'' also occurs in many translations of the [[:en:Old_Testament|Old Testament]] in allusion to Nubia. The ancient [[:en:Hebrew_language|Hebrew]] texts identify Nubia instead as [[:en:Kingdom_of_Kush|Kush]].<ref>Cp. Ezekiel 29:10</ref> However, in the [[:en:New_Testament|New Testament]], the Greek term Aithiops does occur, referring to a servant of the [[:en:Kandake|Kandake]], the queen of Kush.<ref>Acts 8:27</ref>

Following the Hellenic and Biblical traditions, the [[:en:Monumentum_Adulitanum|Monumentum Adulitanum]], a third century inscription belonging to the [[:en:Aksumite_Empire|Aksumite Empire]], indicates that Aksum's then ruler governed an area which was flanked to the west by the territory of Ethiopia and Sasu. The Aksumite King [[:en:Ezana_of_Axum|Ezana]] would eventually conquer Nubia the following century, and the Aksumites thereafter appropriated the designation "Ethiopians" for their own kingdom. In the [[:en:Ge'ez_language|Ge'ez]] version of the Ezana inscription, Aἰθιόποι is equated with the unvocalized ''Ḥbšt'' and ''Ḥbśt'' (Ḥabashat), and denotes for the first time the highland inhabitants of Aksum. This new demonym would subsequently be rendered as '''ḥbs'' ('Aḥbāsh) in [[:en:Sabaic_language|Sabaic]] and as ''Ḥabasha'' in [[:en:Arabic_language|Arabic]].<ref name="Hatke" />

In the 15th-century Ge'ez ''[[:en:Book_of_Aksum|Book of Aksum]]'', the name is ascribed to a legendary individual called ''[[:en:Ityopp'is|Ityopp'is]]''. He was an extra-Biblical son of [[:en:Cush_(Bible)|Cush, son of Ham]], said to have founded the city of [[:en:Axum|Axum]].<ref name="Agrvt">{{cite book|title=Africa Geoscience Review, Volume 10|date=2003|publisher=Rock View International|page=366|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=QWBPAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref>

In English, and generally outside of Ethiopia, the country was once historically known as Abyssinia. This [[:en:Toponym|toponym]] was derived from the Latinized form of the ancient ''Habash''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schoff|first1=Wilfred Harvey|title=The Periplus of the Erythraean Sea: travel and trade in the Indian Ocean|date=1912|publisher=Longmans, Green, and Co.|page=62|url=https://archive.org/stream/periplusoferythr00schouoft#page/62/mode/2up|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>

