=== Prehistory ===
[[File:Homo_Sapiens_Idaltu.JPG|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Homo_Sapiens_Idaltu.JPG|thumb|A ''[[:en:Homo_sapiens_idaltu|Homo sapiens idaltu]]'' hominid skull]]
Several important finds have propelled Ethiopia and the surrounding region to the forefront of&nbsp;[[:en:Palaeontology|palaeontology]]. The oldest [[:en:Hominidae|hominid]] discovered to date in Ethiopia is the 4.2&nbsp;million year old ''[[:en:Ardipithecus|Ardipithicus ramidus]]'' ([[:en:Ardi|Ardi]]) found by [[:en:Tim_D._White|Tim D. White]] in 1994.<ref name="OldestHuman">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/TECH/science/10/01/oldest.human.skeleton/index.html|title=Oldest human skeleton offers new clues to evolution|last=Ansari|first=Azadeh|date=7 October 2009|accessdate=2 March 2011|newspaper=CNN.com/technology}}</ref> The most well known hominid discovery is ''[[:en:Australopithecus_afarensis|Australopithecus afarensis]]'' ([[:en:Lucy_(Australopithecus)|Lucy]]). Known locally as Dinkinesh, the specimen was found in the [[:en:Awash_Valley|Awash Valley]] of Ethiopia's [[:en:Afar_Region|Afar Region]] in 1974 by [[:en:Donald_Johanson|Donald Johanson]], and is one of the most complete and best preserved adult [[:en:Australopithecus|Australopithecine]] fossils ever uncovered. Lucy's taxonomic name refers to the region where the discovery was made. The hominid is estimated to have lived 3.2&nbsp;million years ago.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sn/prehistoric_life/human/human_evolution/mother_of_man1.shtml|title=Mother of man – 3.2 million years ago|date=|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref><ref name="Dinkinesh">{{cite book|title=Lucy's Legacy: The Quest for Human Origins|last2=Wong|first2=Kate|date=2010|publisher=Crown Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-39640-2|pages=8–9|last1=Johanson|first1=Donald C.}}</ref><ref name="iho1">{{cite web|url=https://iho.asu.edu/about/lucys-story|title=Institute of Human Origins: Lucy's Story|last=|first=|date=15 June 2016|accessdate=23 March 2017|website=}}</ref>

Ethiopia is also considered one of the earliest sites of the emergence of [[:en:Anatomically_modern_human|anatomically modern humans]], ''[[:en:Homo_sapiens|Homo sapiens]]''. The oldest of these local fossil finds, the [[:en:Omo_remains|Omo remains]], were excavated in the southwestern [[:en:Omo_Kibish|Omo Kibish]] area and have been dated to the [[:en:Middle_Paleolithic|Middle Paleolithic]], around 200,000 years ago.<ref name="Mcdougall2005">{{Cite journal|first1=I.|last2=Brown|last3=Fleagle|first2=H.|first3=G.|journal=Nature|volume=433|last1=Mcdougall|title=Stratigraphic placement and age of modern humans from Kibish, Ethiopia|issue=7027|pages=733–36|date=Feb 2005|pmid=15716951|doi=10.1038/nature03258|bibcode=2005Natur.433..733M}}</ref> Additionally, skeletons of ''[[:en:Homo_sapiens_idaltu|Homo sapiens idaltu]]'' were found at a site in the [[:en:Middle_Awash|Middle Awash]] valley. Dated to approximately 160,000 years ago, they may represent an extinct subspecies of ''Homo sapiens'', or the immediate ancestors of anatomically modern humans.<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature01669|first3=D.|pmid=12802332|first7=F.|last7=Clark Howell|first6=G.|last6=Suwa|first5=G.D.|last5=Richards|first4=H.|last4=Gilbert|last3=Degusta|title=Pleistocene Homo sapiens from Middle Awash, Ethiopia|first2=B.|last2=Asfaw|first1=T.D.|last1=White|year=2003|pages=742–47|issue=6941|volume=423|journal=Nature|bibcode=2003Natur.423..742W}}</ref> Archaic ''Homo sapiens'' fossils excavated at the [[:en:Jebel_Irhoud|Jebel Irhoud]] site in [[:en:Morocco|Morocco]] have since been dated to an earlier period, about 300,000 years ago,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Callaway|first=Ewan|title=Oldest ''Homo sapiens'' fossil claim rewrites our species' history|url=http://www.nature.com/news/oldest-homo-sapiens-fossil-claim-rewrites-our-species-history-1.22114|date=7 June 2017|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|doi=10.1038/nature.2017.22114|accessdate=5 July 2017}}</ref> while Omo-Kibish I (Omo I) from southern Ethiopia is the oldest anatomically modern Homo sapiens skeleton currently known (196 ± 5 ka).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hammond|first=Ashley S.|last2=Royer|first2=Danielle F.|last3=Fleagle|first3=John G.|date=Jul 2017|title=The Omo-Kibish I pelvis|journal=Journal of Human Evolution|volume=108|pages=199–219|doi=10.1016/j.jhevol.2017.04.004|issn=1095-8606|pmid=28552208}}</ref>

According to linguists, the first [[:en:Afroasiatic_languages|Afroasiatic]]-speaking populations arrived in the region during the ensuing [[:en:Neolithic|Neolithic]] era from the family's proposed [[:en:Afroasiatic_Urheimat|urheimat]] ("original homeland") in the [[:en:Nile_Valley|Nile Valley]],<ref name="Zarins" /> or the [[:en:Near_East|Near East]].<ref name="Aane">{{Cite journal|doi=10.1126/science.1078208|pages=597–603|type=Submitted manuscript|url=http://faculty.bennington.edu/%7Ekwoods/classes/enviro-hist/diamond%20agriculture%20and%20language.pdf|bibcode=2003Sci...300..597D|pmid=12714734|jstor=3834351|year=2003|issue=5619|last1=Diamond|volume=300|journal=Science|title=Farmers and Their Languages: The First Expansions|first2=P.|last2=Bellwood|first1=J.|citeseerx=10.1.1.1013.4523}}</ref> Other scholars propose that the Afroasiatic family developed in situ in the Horn, with its speakers subsequently dispersing from there.<ref name="Blench143144">{{cite book|last1=Blench|first1=R.|title=Archaeology, Language, and the African Past|date=2006|publisher=Rowman Altamira|isbn=978-0-7591-0466-2|pages=143–44|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=esFy3Po57A8C}}</ref>

In 2019, archaeologists discovered a 30,000-year-old [[:en:Middle_Stone_Age|Middle-Stone Age]] rock shelter at the Fincha Habera site in the [[:en:Bale_Mountains|Bale Mountains]] of Ethiopia at an elevation of 3,469 metres above sea level. At this high altitude humans are susceptible both to [[:en:Hypoxemia#Environmental_oxygen|hypoxia]] and to extreme weather. According to a study published in the journal ''[[:en:Science_(journal)|Science]]'', this dwelling is proof of the earliest permanent human occupation at high altitude yet discovered. Thousands of animal bones, hundreds of stone tools, and ancient fireplaces were discovered, revealing a diet that featured giant [[:en:Spalacidae|mole rats]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/08/science/humans-high-altitude-ethiopia.html|title=In the Ethiopian Mountains, Ancient Humans Were Living the High Life|last=Zimmer|first=Carl|date=8 August 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 August 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/found-earliest-evidence-high-altitude-home-humans-180972878/|title=Archaeologists Uncover Evidence of an Ancient High-Altitude Human Dwelling|last=Katz|first=Brigit|website=Smithsonian|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2019/08/ethiopia-provides-the-earliest-evidence-of-people-living-at-altitude/|title=The first people to live at high elevations snacked on giant mole rats|last=Smith|first=Kiona N.|date=9 August 2019|website=Ars Technica|language=en-us|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/earliest-evidence-human-mountaineers.html|title=Earliest Evidence of Human Mountaineers Found in Ethiopia|last=History|first=Charles Q. Choi 2019-08-09T12:59:10Z|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/this-rock-shelter-in-ethiopia-may-be-the-earliest-evide-1837104167|title=This Rock Shelter in Ethiopia May Be the Earliest Evidence of Humans Living in the Mountains|last=Dvorsky|first=George|website=Gizmodo|language=en-US|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Science_News/2019/08/09/Earliest-evidence-of-high-altitude-living-found-in-Ethiopia/9561565318908/|title=Earliest evidence of high-altitude living found in Ethiopia|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Miehe|first8=Agazi|pmid=31395781|issn=0036-8075|doi=10.1126/science.aaw8942|pages=583–587|issue=6453|volume=365|language=en|journal=Science|title=Middle Stone Age foragers resided in high elevations of the glaciated Bale Mountains, Ethiopia|date=9 August 2019|first9=Thomas|last9=Nauss|last8=Negash|first=Georg|first7=Sileshi|last7=Nemomissa|first6=Heinz|last6=Veit|first5=Ralf|last5=Vogelsang|first4=Zerihun|last4=Woldu|first3=Wolfgang|last3=Zech|first2=Lars|last2=Opgenoorth|bibcode=2019Sci...365..583O}}</ref>

Evidence of some of the earliest known stone-tipped projectile weapons (a characteristic tool of ''[[:en:Homo_sapiens|Homo sapiens]]''), the stone tips of javelins or throwing spears, were discovered in 2013 at the Ethiopian site of [[:en:Gademotta|Gademotta]], and date to around 279,000 years ago.<ref name="SahlePLOS1">{{Cite journal|last1=Sahle|editor1-last=Petraglia|pmc=3827237|pmid=24236011|year=2013|pages=e78092|issue=11|volume=8|journal=PLOS ONE|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0078092|title=Earliest Stone-Tipped Projectiles from the Ethiopian Rift Date to >279,000 Years Ago|editor1-first=Michael D|first7=B.|first1=Y.|last7=Atnafu|first6=A.|last6=Negash|first5=L. E.|last5=Morgan|first4=J. C.|last4=Sealy|first3=D. R.|last3=Braun|first2=W. K.|last2=Hutchings|bibcode=2013PLoSO...878092S}}</ref> In 2019, further evidence of Middle Stone Age complex projectile weapons was found at Aduma, also in Ethiopia, dated 100,000-80,000 years ago, in the form of points considered likely to belong to darts delivered by spear throwers.<ref name="Sahle">{{Cite journal|title=Assessment of complex projectiles in the early Late Pleistocene at Aduma, Ethiopia|journal=PLOS One|volume=14|issue=5|pages=e0216716|year=2018|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0216716|pmid=31071181|pmc=6508696|vauthors=Sahle Y, Brooks AS}}</ref>

=== Antiquity ===
{{Main|Dʿmt|Kingdom of Aksum}}
[[File:ET_Axum_asv2018-01_img37_Stelae_Park.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:ET_Axum_asv2018-01_img37_Stelae_Park.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Obelisk_of_Aksum|Obelisk of Aksum]]]]
Around the 8th century BC, a kingdom known as [[:en:Dʿmt|Dʿmt]] was established in [[:en:Tigray_Region|Tigray]], in northern Ethiopia, and [[:en:Eritrea|Eritrea]]. The polity's capital was located at [[:en:Yeha|Yeha]], in northern Ethiopia. Most modern historians consider this civilization to be a native Ethiopian one, although [[:en:Sabaeans|Sabaean]]-influenced because of the latter's hegemony of the Red Sea.<ref name="Munro-Hay57" />

Other scholars regard Dʿmt as the result of a union of Afroasiatic-speaking cultures of the Cushitic and Semitic branches; namely, local Agaw peoples and Sabaeans from [[:en:South_Arabia|South Arabia]]. However, [[:en:Ge'ez_language|Ge'ez]], the ancient Semitic language of Ethiopia, is thought to have developed independently from [[:en:Sabaean_language|Sabaean]], one of the [[:en:South_Semitic_languages|South Semitic languages]]. As early as 2000 BC, other Semitic speakers were living in Ethiopia and Eritrea where Ge'ez developed.<ref>Tamrat, Taddesse (1972) ''Church and State in Ethiopia: 1270–1527''. London: Oxford University Press, pp. 5–13.</ref><ref>Uhlig, Siegbert (ed.) (2005) ''[[Encyclopaedia Aethiopica]]'', "Ge'ez". Wiesbaden: Harrassowitz Verlag, p. 732.</ref> Sabaean influence is now thought to have been minor, limited to a few localities, and disappearing after a few decades or a century. It may have been a trading or military colony in alliance with the Ethiopian civilization of Dʿmt or some other proto-Aksumite state.<ref name="Munro-Hay57" />
[[File:KingEndybisEthiopia227-235CE.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:KingEndybisEthiopia227-235CE.jpg|left|thumb|[[:en:Aksumite_currency|Aksumite currency]] of the Aksumite king [[:en:Endubis|Endubis]], 227–35, at the [[:en:British_Museum|British Museum]]. The inscriptions in [[:en:Ancient_Greek|Ancient Greek]] read "ΑΧΩΜΙΤΩ ΒΑΣΙΛΕΥΣ" ("KING OF AXUM") and "ΕΝΔΥΒΙΣ ΒΑΣΙΛΕΥΣ" ("KING ENDUBIS"), the Greek language was the [[:en:Lingua_franca|lingua franca]] by that time so the [[:en:Axumite_kings|Axumite kings]] used it in coins to simplify foreign trade.]]
After the fall of Dʿmt during the fourth century BC, the Ethiopian plateau came to be dominated by smaller successor kingdoms. In the first century AD, the [[:en:Kingdom_of_Aksum|Kingdom of Aksum]] emerged in what is now [[:en:Tigray_Region|Tigray]] and Eritrea. According to the medieval ''[[:en:Book_of_Aksum|Book of Aksum]]'', the kingdom's first capital, Mazaber, was built by Itiyopis, son of Cush.<ref name="Agrvt" /> Aksum would later at times extend its rule into Yemen on the other side of the Red Sea.<ref>{{cite book|first=David W.|last=Phillipson|title=Ancient Ethiopia. Aksum: Its Antecedents and Successors|publisher=The British Museum Press|year=1998|pages=7, 48–50|isbn=978-0-7141-2763-7}}</ref> The Persian prophet [[:en:Mani_(prophet)|Mani]] listed Aksum with Rome, Persia, and China as one of the four great powers of his era, during the 3rd century.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Munro-Hay|Munro-Hay]], p. 13</ref>

Around 316 AD, [[:en:Frumentius|Frumentius]] and his brother Edesius from [[:en:Tyre,_Lebanon|Tyre]] accompanied their uncle on a voyage to Ethiopia. When the vessel stopped at a Red Sea port, the natives killed all the travellers except the two brothers, who were taken to the court as [[:en:Slavery_in_Ethiopia|slaves]]. They were given positions of trust by the monarch, and they converted members of the royal court to Christianity. Frumentius became the first bishop of Aksum.<ref name="isbn0-313-32273-2">{{cite book|author=Adejumobi, Saheed A.|title=The history of Ethiopia|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, CN|year=2007|page=171|isbn=978-0-313-32273-0|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3Un6_LGIEyQC&pg=PA171}}</ref> A [[:en:Aksumite_currency|coin]] dated to 324 shows that Ethiopia was the second country to officially adopt Christianity (after [[:en:Armenia|Armenia]] did so in 301), although the religion may have been at first confined to court circles; it was the first major power to do so.

The weakened Axumite dynasty came to an end in the 9th century when Yodit defeated the last king of the dynasty. Empress Yodit's reign, which lasted for 40 years, aimed to abolish Christianity (a religion first accepted by King Ezana of the Axumite dynasty) by burning down churches and crucifying people who remained faithful to the orthodox Tewahedo church, which at the time was considered as the religion of the state. The Empress tried to force many people to change their religion and destroyed much historical heritage of the Axumite dynasty earning her the epithet of Yodit Gudit (in Amharic ዮዲት ጉዲት). Her reign finally came to an end in 912 following her defeat by the first leader of the Zagwe dynasty.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tegelachen|last=Haile Mariam|first=Mengistu|publisher=corneal Mengistu Haile Mariam|year=2004|location=Ethiopia|pages=16–21}}</ref> The reign of the Zagwe dynasty came to an end by the rise of [[:en:Yekuno_Amlak|Yekuno Amlak]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Greville Stewart Parker Freeman-Grenville|author2=Stuart Christopher Munro-Hay|title=Islam: An Illustrated History|date=2006|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4411-6533-6|pages=177–78|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=3fKoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA177}}</ref>

=== During Muhammad's era ===
{{Main|Migration to Abyssinia|List of expeditions of Muhammad|Hegira}}The first interaction that the Islamic Prophet [[:en:Muhammad|Muhammad]] had with Ethiopia was during the reign of [[:en:Aṣḥama_ibn_Abjar|Aṣḥama ibn Abjar]], who was at the time the Emperor of [[:en:Aksum|Aksum]] and gave refuge to several [[:en:Muslim|Muslims]] in the [[:en:Kingdom_of_Aksum|Kingdom of Aksum]] in 614 AD.<ref>[[Fiaccadori, Gianfranco]] (2005) "Ellä Säham" in ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'', vol. 2, Wiesbaden</ref> According to other authors, Ashama may have been the same person as king [[:en:Armah|Armah]], or his father or son.<ref>Hable Sellassie, Sergew (1972). ''Ancient and Medieval Ethiopian History to 1270''. Addis Ababa: United Printers, p. 185.</ref> Taddesse Tamrat records that the inhabitants of [[:en:Wiqro|Wiqro]], where the ruler is known as ''Ashamat al-Negashi'', claim that his tomb is located in their village.<ref>Tamrat, Taddesse (1972) ''Church and State in Ethiopia (1270–1527)''. Oxford: Clarendon Press, p. 34.</ref><ref>Zakaria, Rafiq (1991) ''Muhammad and The Quran'', New Delhi: Penguin Books, pp. 403–04. {{ISBN|0-14-014423-4}}</ref>

Muhammad's second interaction with Ethiopia was during the [[:en:Expedition_of_Zaid_ibn_Haritha_(Hisma)|Expedition of Zaid ibn Haritha]], when he sent [[:en:Amr_bin_Umayyah_al-Damri|Amr bin Umayyah al-Damri]] to the King of Ethiopia (then Abyssinia).<ref>{{cite book|author1=Al-Mubarakpuri, Safiur-Rahman|title=الرحيق المختوم: بحث في السيرة النبوية على صاحبها افضل الصلاة و السلام|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-ppPqzawIrIC&pg=PA221|date=2002|publisher=ideas4islam|page=221}}</ref>

=== Middle Ages ===
{{Main|Zagwe dynasty|Ethiopian Empire}}
[[File:Lebna_Dengel.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lebna_Dengel.png|thumb|[[:en:Dawit_II|Dawit II]] (Lebna Dengel), [[:en:Emperor_of_Ethiopia|Emperor of Ethiopia]] (r. 1507–1540) and a member of the [[:en:Solomonic_dynasty|Solomonic dynasty]]]]
The [[:en:Zagwe_dynasty|Zagwe dynasty]] ruled many parts of present-day Ethiopia and Eritrea between the early 12th and late 13th century. The name of the [[:en:Dynasty|dynasty]] is derived from the Cushitic-speaking [[:en:Agaw_people|Agaw]] of northern Ethiopia. From 1270 AD until the ''[[:en:Zemene_Mesafint|Zemene Mesafint]]'' (Age of Princes), the [[:en:Solomonic_dynasty|Solomonic dynasty]] governed the [[:en:Ethiopian_Empire|Ethiopian Empire]].<ref>A.K. Irvine, "Review: The Different Collections of Nägś Hymns in Ethiopic Literature and Their Contributions." ''Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London''. School of Oriental and African Studies, 1985.</ref>

In the early 15th century, Ethiopia sought to make diplomatic contact with European kingdoms for the first time since the Aksumite era. A letter from [[:en:Henry_IV_of_England|Henry IV of England]] to the Emperor of Abyssinia survives.<ref>Mortimer, Ian (2007) ''The Fears of Henry IV'', p. 111. {{ISBN|1-84413-529-2}}</ref> In 1428, [[:en:Yeshaq_I|Yeshaq I]] sent two emissaries to [[:en:Alfonso_V_of_Aragon|Alfonso V of Aragon]], who sent return emissaries. They failed to complete the return trip.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Beshah|Beshah]], pp. 13–14.</ref> The first continuous relations with a European country began in 1508 with Portugal under [[:en:Dawit_II|Dawit II]] (Lebna Dengel), who had just inherited the throne from his father.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Beshah|Beshah]], p. 25.</ref> In 1487, King John II of Portugal sent two emissaries to the Orient, Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva. Afonso would die on this mission.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=A History of Portuguese Overseas Expansion 1400–1668|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=HDODAgAAQBAJ&redir_esc=y|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|website=}}</ref>
