=== The Portuguese allied ===
This proved to be an important development, for when the Empire was subjected to an occupation led by the [[:en:Adal_Sultanate|Adal Sultanate]]'s general and [[:en:Imam|imam]], [[:en:Ahmad_ibn_Ibrahim_al-Ghazi|Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi]] (called "''Grañ''&#x2009;" "the Left-handed"), Portugal assisted the Ethiopian emperor by sending weapons and four hundred men, who helped his son [[:en:Gelawdewos|Gelawdewos]] defeat Ahmad and re-establish his rule.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Beshah|Beshah]], pp. 45–52.</ref>

This [[:en:Abyssinian–Adal_War|Abyssinian–Adal War]] was also one of the first proxy wars in the region, as the [[:en:Ottoman_Empire|Ottoman Empire]] and [[:en:Portugal|Portugal]] took sides in the conflict. When Emperor [[:en:Susenyos_I|Susenyos I]] converted to [[:en:Catholic_Church|Roman Catholicism]] in 1624, years of revolt and civil unrest followed, resulting in thousands of deaths.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Beshah|Beshah]], pp. 91, 97–104.</ref> The [[:en:Society_of_Jesus|Jesuit missionaries]] had offended the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo]] faith of the local Ethiopians. In June 1632, [[:en:Fasilides|Fasilides]], Susenyos' son, declared the state religion again to be the Ethiopian Orthodoxy. He expelled the Jesuit missionaries and other Europeans.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Beshah|Beshah]], p. 105.</ref><ref>van Donzel, Emeri (2005) "Fasilädäs" in Siegbert von Uhlig, ed., ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica: D-Ha''. Wiesbaden:Harrassowitz Verlag. p. 500.</ref>

=== Aussa Sultanate ===
{{Main|Sultanate of Aussa|Mudaito Dynasty}}The [[:en:Sultanate_of_Aussa|Sultanate of Aussa]] or "Afar Sultanate" succeeded the earlier [[:en:Imamate_of_Aussa|Imamate of Aussa]]. The latter polity had come into existence in 1577 when [[:en:Muhammed_Jasa|Muhammed Jasa]] moved his capital from [[:en:Harar|Harar]] to Aussa ([[:en:Asaita|Asaita]]) with the split of the [[:en:Adal_Sultanate|Adal Sultanate]] into the Sultanate of Aussa and the [[:en:Sultanate_of_Harar|Sultanate of Harar]]. At some point after 1672, the Sultanate of Aussa declined and temporarily came to an end in conjunction with Imam [[:en:Umar_Din_bin_Adam|Umar Din bin Adam]]'s recorded ascension to the throne.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Abir|Abir]], p. 23 n.1.</ref>

The Sultanate was subsequently re-established by [[:en:Kedafu|Kedafu]] around the year 1734. It was thereafter ruled by his [[:en:Mudaito_Dynasty|Mudaito Dynasty]].<ref>[[Ethiopia#Abir|Abir]], pp. 23–26.</ref> The primary symbol of the Sultan was a silver [[:en:Baton_(military)|baton]], which was considered to have magical properties.<ref>Trimingham, J. Spencer (1952) ''Islam in Ethiopia''. Oxford: Geoffrey Cumberlege for the University Press. p. 262.</ref>

=== Zemene Mesafint ===
{{Main|Zemene Mesafint}}
[[File:Flag_of_Ethiopia_(1897).svg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Flag_of_Ethiopia_(1897).svg|left|thumb|1897 [[:en:Flag_of_Ethiopia|Ethiopian flag]] with the [[:en:Lion_of_Judah|Lion of Judah]]]]
Between 1755 and 1855, Ethiopia experienced a period of isolation referred to as the ''[[:en:Zemene_Mesafint|Zemene Mesafint]]'' or "Age of Princes". The Emperors became figureheads, controlled by regional lords and noblemen like [[:en:Ras_(title)|''Ras'']] [[:en:Mikael_Sehul|Mikael Sehul]] of [[:en:Tigray_Province|Tigray]], [[:en:Ras_(title)|''Ras'']] [[:en:Wolde_Selassie|Wolde Selassie]] of Tigray, and by the Were Sheh[[:en:Yejju_Oromo_tribe|Yejju Oromo dynasty]], such as ''Ras'' [[:en:Gugsa_of_Yejju|Gugsa of Yejju]]. Prior to the Zemene Mesafint, King Iyoas had introduced Oromo as the language of the court from Amharic to [[:en:Oromo_language|Afaan Oromo]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Pankhurst, Richard|title=The Ethiopian Royal Chronicles|location=London|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1967|pages=139–143}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gargaaraoromopc.org/OPC_Program.aspx|title=Political Program of the Oromo People's Congress (OPC)|publisher=Gargaaraoromopc.org|date=23 April 1996|accessdate=16 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307213227/http://gargaaraoromopc.org/OPC_Program.aspx|archivedate=7 March 2009}}</ref>
[[File:Téwodros_II.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:T%C3%A9wodros_II.jpg|thumb|Emperor [[:en:Tewodros_II_of_Ethiopia|Tewodros II of Ethiopia]]]]
Ethiopian isolationism ended following a British mission that concluded an alliance between the two nations, but it was not until 1855 that the Amhara kingdoms of northern Ethiopia (Gonder, Gojam, Shoa) were briefly united after the power of the Emperor was restored beginning with the reign of [[:en:Tewodros_II|Tewodros II]].  Tewodros had been born in [[:en:Begemder|Begemder]] from a nobleman of [[:en:Qwara_Province|Qwara]], where the [[:en:Qwara_dialect|Qwara dialect]] of the Agaw language is spoken.

Upon his ascent, he began [[:en:Modernization_theory|modernizing]] Ethiopia and recentralizing power in the Emperor. Ethiopia began to take part in world affairs once again.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://africanhistory.oxfordre.com/view/10.1093/acrefore/9780190277734.001.0001/acrefore-9780190277734-e-279|chapter=Ethiopia in the Nineteenth Century|last=Tibebu|first=Teshale|date=June 2018|title=Oxford Research Encyclopedia of African History|access-date=|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780190277734.013.279}}</ref>

But Tewodros suffered several rebellions inside his empire. Northern Oromo militias, Tigrayan rebellion, and the constant incursion of Ottoman Empire and Egyptian forces near the Red Sea brought the weakening and the final downfall of Tewodros II. He killed himself in 1868 during his last fight with the [[:en:British_Expedition_to_Abyssinia|British Expedition to Abyssinia]] at the [[:en:Battle_of_Magdala|Battle of Magdala]].

After Tewodros' death, [[:en:Tekle_Giyorgis_II|Tekle Giyorgis II]] was proclaimed Emperor but was defeated in the Battles of Zulawu (21 June 1871) and Adua (11 July 1871).
[[File:Yohannesson.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Yohannesson.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|[[:en:Emperor_of_Ethiopia|Emperor]] [[:en:Yohannes_IV|Yohannes IV]] led Ethiopian troops during the battles of [[:en:Battle_of_Gallabat|Galabat]], [[:en:Battle_of_Gundet|Gundet]] and [[:en:Battle_of_Gura|Gura]].]]
The victorious Mercha Kassai was subsequently declared [[:en:Yohannes_IV|Yohannes IV]] on 21 January 1872. In 1875 and 1876, Turkish/Egyptian forces, accompanied by many European and American 'advisors', twice invaded Abyssinia but were initially defeated: once at the Battle of Gundet losing 800 men, and then in the second invasion, decisively defeated by Emperor Yohannes IV at the [[:en:Battle_of_Gura|Battle of Gura]] on 7{{nbsp}}March 1875, where the invading forces lost at least 3000 men by death or captured.<ref>[http://vislardica.com/VisImperica/Wars/vi_egypt_abyssinia.htm The Egyptians in Abyssinia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111226155100/http://vislardica.com/VisImperica/Wars/vi_egypt_abyssinia.htm|date=26 December 2011}}. Vislardica.com. Retrieved on 3 March 2012.</ref> From 1885 to 1889, Ethiopia joined the [[:en:Mahdist_War|Mahdist War]] allied to Britain, Turkey, and Egypt against the Sudanese Mahdist State. In 1887 Menelik king of [[:en:Shewa|Shewa]] invaded the [[:en:Emirate_of_Harar|Emirate of Harar]] after his victory at the [[:en:Battle_of_Chelenqo|Battle of Chelenqo]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=CAULK|first1=RICHARD|title=The Occupation of Harar: January 1887|journal=Journal of Ethiopian Studies|year=1971|volume=9|issue=2|pages=1–20|jstor=41967469}}</ref> On 10 March 1889, Yohannes IV was killed by the Sudanese Khalifah Abdullah's army whilst leading his army in the [[:en:Battle_of_Gallabat|Battle of Gallabat]] (also called Battle of Metemma).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dictionary of African historical biography|last=Lipschutz|first=Mark|date=1986|publisher=University of California Press|others=Rasmussen, R. Kent|isbn=978-0-520-06611-3|edition=2nd ed., expanded and updated|location=Berkeley|page=1|oclc=14069361}}</ref>

=== From Menelik II to Adwa (1889–1913) ===
[[File:Emperor_Menelik_II.png|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Emperor_Menelik_II.png|thumb|Emperor [[:en:Menelik_II|Menelik II]], former Governor of [[:en:Shewa|Shewa]]]]
Ethiopia in roughly its current form began under the reign of [[:en:Menelik_II|Menelik II]], who was Emperor from 1889 until his death in 1913. From his base in the central province of [[:en:Shewa|Shewa]], Menelik set out to annex territories to the south, east and west,<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/01436599814415|title=Regionalism and democracy in Ethiopia|journal=Third World Quarterly|volume=19|issue=2|pages=191–204|year=1998|last1=Young|first1=J.|jstor=3993156}}</ref> areas inhabited by the Oromo, [[:en:Sidama_people|Sidama]], Gurage, [[:en:Welayta_people|Welayta]], and other peoples.<ref name="igg">International Crisis Group, "Ethnic Federalism and its Discontents". Issue 153 of ''ICG Africa'' report (4 September 2009) p. 2; Italy lost over 4,600 nationals in this battle.</ref> He did this with the help of ''Ras'' [[:en:Gobana_Dacche|Gobana Dacche]]'s Shewan Oromo militia, which occupied lands that had not been held since Ahmad ibn Ibrahim al-Ghazi's war, as well as other areas that had never been under Ethiopian sovereignty.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Great Britain and Ethiopia 1897–1910: Competition for Empire|author=Keefer, Edward C.|journal=International Journal of African Studies|volume=6|issue=3|pages=468–74|year=1973|jstor=216612|doi=10.2307/216612}}</ref> Menelik's campaign against Oromos outside his army was largely in retaliation for centuries of Oromo expansionism and the ''Zemene Mesafint'', a period during which a succession of Oromo feudal rulers dominated the highlanders.<ref name="Kanno">{{cite book|last=Martial (de Salviac, père.)|first=Ayalew Kanno|title=An Ancient People in the State of Menelik: The Oromo (said to be of Gallic Origin) Great African Nation|year=2005|publisher=Ayalew Kanno|isbn=978-1-59975-189-4|page=8|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pZpyAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> Chief among these was the Yejju dynasty, which included [[:en:Aligaz_of_Yejju|Aligaz of Yejju]] and his brother [[:en:Ali_I_of_Yejju|Ali I of Yejju]]. Ali I founded the town of [[:en:Debre_Tabor|Debre Tabor]] in the [[:en:Amhara_Region|Amhara Region]], which became the dynasty's capital.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Abir|Abir]], p. 30</ref>
[[File:Menelik_campaign_map_1_3.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Menelik_campaign_map_1_3.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The conquests of Emperor [[:en:Yohannes_IV|Yohannes IV]], Negus [[:en:Menelik_II|Menelik]] and general [[:en:Ras_Alula|Ras Alula]] in 1879-1889]]
Menelik was born from King Hailemelekot of Shewa and his mother Ejegayehu Lema Adeyamo who was a servant in the royal household.<ref name="Menelik2">[https://web.archive.org/web/20160805155714/https://business.highbeam.com/3548/article-1G1-55800557/ethiopia-personalities-millennium-emperor-menelik-ii "Ethiopia's Personalities Of The Millennium – Emperor Menelik II."], highbeam.com Published on 21 September 1999 Retrieved 10 April 2015</ref> He had been born at Angolala in an Oromo area and had lived his first twelve years with Shewan Oromos with whom he thus had much in common.<ref name="Menelik1">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Greenfield|first=Richard|title=Ethiopia: A New Political History|url=https://books.google.com/?id=hGUMAQAAIAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Praeger}}, p. 97.</ref> During his reign, Menelik II advanced road construction, electricity and education; the development of a central taxation system and the foundation and building of the city of Addis Ababa—which became the capital of Shewa Province in 1881. After he ascended to the throne in 1889, it was renamed Addis Ababa, the new capital of Abyssinia.

For his leadership, despite opposition from more traditional elements of society, Menelik II is heralded as a national hero. Menelik had signed the Treaty of Wichale with Italy in May 1889 in which Italy would recognize Ethiopia's sovereignty so long as Italy could control an area north of Ethiopia (now part of modern Eritrea). In return, Italy was to provide Menelik with weapons and support him as emperor. The Italians used the time between the signing of the treaty and its ratification by the Italian government to expand their territorial claims. This conflict erupted in the [[:en:Battle_of_Adwa|Battle of Adwa]] on 1{{nbsp}}March 1896 in which Italy's colonial forces were defeated by the Ethiopians.<ref name="igg" /><ref>Negash, Tekeste. [https://books.google.com/books?id=txsoS39UplMC Eritrea and Ethiopia : The Federal Experience]. Uppsala, Sweden: Nordiska Afrikainstitutet (2005) {{ISBN|1-56000-992-6}} pp. 13–14</ref>

About a third of the population died in the [[:en:Famines_in_Ethiopia|Great Ethiopian Famine]] (1888 to 1892).<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,966291-3,00.html Famine Hunger stalks Ethiopia once again – and aid groups fear the worst]. ''Time''. 21 December 1987</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1093/jhmas/XXI.2.95|title=The Great Ethiopian Famine of 1888–1892: A New Assessment|journal=Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences|issue=2|pages=95–124|year=1966|last1=Pankhurst|first1=R.|volume=21|pmid=5326887}}</ref>

=== Haile Selassie I era (1916–1974) and Italian Ethiopia ===
{{Main|Italian Ethiopia|Italian East Africa|Arbegnoch|Black Lions}}
[[File:Addis_Ababa-8e00855u.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Addis_Ababa-8e00855u.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Haile_Selassie|Haile Selassie]] at his study at the palace]]
[[File:RAS_Abissini_Pd-italy-005.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:RAS_Abissini_Pd-italy-005.jpg|thumb|Ras [[:en:Seyoum_Mengesha|Seyoum Mengesha]], Ras Ghetacciù Abaté and Ras Kebbedé Guebret with [[:en:Benito_Mussolini|Benito Mussolini]] on 6{{nbsp}}February 1937 in Rome, Italy, after the Italian occupation of Ethiopia]]
The early 20th century was marked by the reign of Emperor [[:en:Haile_Selassie|Haile Selassie]] ''(Ras Tafari)''. Haile Selassie I was born to parents with ethnic links to three of Ethiopia's Afroasiatic-speaking populations: the ''Oromo'' and ''Amhara'', the country's two largest ethnic groups, as well as the [[:en:Gurage_people|Gurage]]. He came to power after [[:en:Iyasu_V|Iyasu V]] was deposed, and undertook [[:en:Modernization_under_Haile_Selassie_I|a nationwide modernization campaign]] from 1916, when he was made a ''Ras'' and Regent (''Inderase'') for the [[:en:Queen_regnant|Empress Regnant]], [[:en:Zewditu|Zewditu]], and became the ''de facto'' ruler of the Ethiopian Empire. Following Zewditu's death, on 2{{nbsp}}November 1930, he succeeded her as emperor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merit.unu.edu/publications/publications-search/|title=U.S. and Soviet Foreign Aid during the Cold War – A Case Study of Ethiopia|last=Broich|first=Tobias|date=2017|website=The United Nations University – Maastricht Economic and Social Research Institute on Innovation and Technology (UNU-MERIT)|access-date=}}</ref>

The independence of Ethiopia was interrupted by the [[:en:Second_Italo-Ethiopian_War|Second Italo-Ethiopian War]], beginning when it was invaded by [[:en:Kingdom_of_Italy#Fascist_regime_(1922%E2%80%931943)|Fascist Italy]] in early October 1935, and Italian occupation of the country (1936–1941).<ref>Clapham, Christopher (2005) "Ḫaylä Śəllase" in Siegbert von Uhlig, ed., ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica: D-Ha''. Wiesbaden:Harrassowitz Verlag. pp. 1062–63.</ref> During this time, Haile Selassie appealed to the [[:en:League_of_Nations|League of Nations]] in 1935, delivering an address that made him a worldwide figure, and the 1935 [[:en:Time_Person_of_the_Year|''Time'' Man of the Year]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,755559-1,00.html|title=Man of the Year|date=6 January 1936|magazine=TIME|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref> As the majority of the Ethiopian population lived in rural towns, Italy faced continued resistance and ambushes in urban centres throughout its occupation. Haile Selassie fled into exile in [[:en:Fairfield_House,_Bath|Fairfield House, Bath]], England. Mussolini was able to proclaim [[:en:Italian_Ethiopia|Italian Ethiopia]] and the assumption of the imperial title by the Italian king [[:en:Vittorio_Emanuele_III|Vittorio Emanuele III]].<ref>Leggere la storia, Dai Nazionalismi alla Seconda Guerra Mondiale. Editore: Einaudi Scuola; Autori: Manzoni Occhipinti Cereda Innocenti; pp. 302–03 La politica coloniale : La proclamazione dell'impero.</ref>

In 1937, the Italian massacre of [[:en:Yekatit_12|Yekatit 12]] took place, in which as many as 30,000 civilians were killed and many others imprisoned.<ref name=":02">{{Cite book|last=Campbell|first=Ian|title=The Addis Ababa Massacre: Italy's National Shame|year=2017|isbn=978-1-84904-692-3|location=London|oclc=999629248}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Barker|first=A. J.|title=The Civilising Mission: The Italo-Ethiopian War 1935–6|publisher=Cassell|year=1968|isbn=978-0-304-93201-6|location=London|pages=292-293}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Martel|first=Gordon|title=The origins of the Second World War reconsidered : A.J.P. Taylor and the Historians|publisher=Routledge|year=1999|isbn=0-203-01024-8|edition=2nd|location=London|pages=188|oclc=252806536}}</ref> This massacre was a reprisal for the attempted assassination [[:en:Rodolfo_Graziani|Rodolfo Graziani]], the viceroy of [[:en:Italian_East_Africa|Italian East Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=David|first=Forgacs|date=September 2016|title=Italian Massacres in Occupied Ethiopia|url=https://arb.crasc.dz/index.php/fr/37-volume-12-n%C2%B0-02-septembre-2016/313-italian-massacres-in-occupied-ethiopia1|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171202132955/http://arb.crasc.dz/index.php/fr/37-volume-12-n%C2%B0-02-septembre-2016/313-italian-massacres-in-occupied-ethiopia1|archive-date=2 December 2017|access-date=|website=Revue Africaine des Livres – Centre de Recherche en Antropologie Sociale et Culturelle}}</ref>

The Italians made investments in Ethiopian infrastructure development during their occupation. They created the so-called "imperial road" between Addis Ababa and Massaua.<ref>[http://media.tecnici.it/file/novecento/autocamionale_assab_addis-abeba.pdf 1940 Article on the special road Addis Ababa-Assab and map (in Italian)]</ref> More than 900&nbsp;km of railways were reconstructed, dams and hydroelectric plants were built, and many public and private companies were established. The Italian government abolished [[:en:Slavery_in_Ethiopia|slavery]], a practice that existed in the country for centuries.<ref name="Accessed 15 May 2008" />

Following the entry of Italy into World War II, [[:en:British_Empire|British Empire]] forces, together with the ''[[:en:Arbegnoch|Arbegnoch]]'' (literally, "patriots", referring to armed resistance soldiers) restored the sovereignty of Ethiopia in the course of the [[:en:East_African_Campaign_(World_War_II)|East African Campaign]] in 1941. An [[:en:Italian_guerrilla_war_in_Ethiopia|Italian guerrilla warfare campaign]] continued until 1943. This was followed by British recognition of Ethiopia's full [[:en:Sovereignty|sovereignty]], without any special British privileges, when the [[:en:Anglo-Ethiopian_Agreement|Anglo-Ethiopian Agreement]] was signed in December 1944.<ref>Clapham, "Ḫaylä Śəllase", ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica'', p. 1063.</ref> Under the peace treaty of 1947, Italy recognised the sovereignty and independence of Ethiopia.

On 26 August 1942, Haile Selassie issued a proclamation that removed Ethiopia's legal basis for slavery.<ref>Hinks, Peter P.; McKivigan, John R. and Williams, R. Owen (2007). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_SeZrcBqt-YC Encyclopedia of Antislavery and Abolition]'', Greenwood Publishing Group, p. 248. {{ISBN|0-313-33143-X}}.</ref> Ethiopia had between two and four million slaves in the early 20th century, out of a total population of about eleven million.{{sfn|Campbell|Miers|Miller|2007|p=219}}

In 1952, Haile Selassie orchestrated a [[:en:Federation_of_Ethiopia_and_Eritrea|federation with Eritrea]]. He dissolved this in 1962 and [[:en:Annexation|annexed]] Eritrea, resulting in the [[:en:Eritrean_War_of_Independence|Eritrean War of Independence]]. Haile Selassie played a leading role in the formation of the [[:en:Organisation_of_African_Unity|Organisation of African Unity]] (OAU) in 1963.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blackpast.org/1963-haile-selassie-towards-african-unity|title=(1963) Haile Selassie, "Towards African Unity"|date=7 August 2009|website=BlackPast.org|access-date=}}</ref>

Opinion within Ethiopia turned against Haile Selassie I owing to the worldwide [[:en:1973_oil_crisis|1973 oil crisis]]. This oil crisis caused a sharp increase in gasoline prices starting on 13 February 1974; food shortages; uncertainty regarding the succession; border wars; and discontent in the middle class created through modernization.<ref name="Black Book">''[[The Black Book of Communism]]'', pp. 687–95</ref> The high gasoline prices motivated taxi drivers and teachers to go on strike on 18 February 1974, and students and workers in Addis Ababa began demonstrating against the government on 20 February 1974.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Valdes Vivo|Valdes Vivo]], p. 115.</ref> The feudal oligarchical cabinet of Akilou Habte Wolde was toppled, and a new government was formed with [[:en:Endelkachew_Makonnen|Endelkachew Makonnen]] serving as Prime Minister.<ref>[[Ethiopia#Valdes Vivo|Valdes Vivo]], p. 21.</ref>

=== Communist era (1974–1991) ===
{{see also|Ethiopia–Russia relations#1974 revolution|Derg|People's Democratic Republic of Ethiopia|Ethiopian Civil War|Eritrean War of Independence|1983–85 famine in Ethiopia}}
[[File:EPRP.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:EPRP.jpg|thumb|The [[:en:Ethiopian_People's_Revolutionary_Party|Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Party]] (EPRP) clashed with the [[:en:Derg|Derg]] during the [[:en:Qey_Shibir|Qey Shibir]]]]
Haile Selassie's rule ended on 12 September 1974, when he was deposed by the [[:en:Derg|Derg]], a Soviet-backed [[:en:Marxism–Leninism|Marxist–Leninist]] military dictatorship led by [[:en:Mengistu_Haile_Mariam|Mengistu Haile Mariam]].<ref>[[Ethiopia#Valdes Vivo|Valdes Vivo]], p. 25.</ref> The new [[:en:Provisional_Military_Administrative_Council|Provisional Military Administrative Council]] established a [[:en:One-party|one-party]] [[:en:Communist_state|communist state]] in March 1975.<ref>{{cite book|title=Africa South of the Sahara 2003|last=Eur|publisher=Psychology Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1-85743-131-5|location=|page=383}}</ref>

The ensuing government suffered several coups, uprisings, wide-scale drought, and a huge refugee problem. In 1977, Somalia, which had previously been receiving assistance and arms from the [[:en:Soviet_Union|USSR]], invaded Ethiopia in the [[:en:Ogaden_War|Ogaden War]], capturing part of the Ogaden region. Ethiopia recovered it after it began receiving massive military aid from the USSR, [[:en:Cuba|Cuba]], [[:en:South_Yemen|South Yemen]], [[:en:East_Germany|East Germany]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Dagne|first=Haile Gabriel|title=The commitment of the German Democratic Republic in Ethiopia: a study based on Ethiopian sources|publisher=Global Lit.|year=2006|location=London|isbn=978-3-8258-9535-8}}</ref> and [[:en:North_Korea|North Korea]]. This included around 15,000 Cuban combat troops.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_01_08.html|title=The Mengistu Regime and Its Impact|last=|first=|date=|website=Library of Congress|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1978/03/05/the-superpowers-and-the-ogaden-war/00f60ef2-01b4-4cd3-8c5f-e545df388def/?|title=The Superpowers and the Ogaden War|last=Oberdorfer|first=Don|date=March 1978|newspaper=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>

In 1977–78, up to 500,000 were killed as a result of the [[:en:Qey_Shibir|Red Terror]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/575405.stm|title=US admits helping Mengistu escape|date=22 December 1999|website=BBC|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref> [[:en:Resettlement_and_villagization_in_Ethiopia|from forced deportations]] or from the use of hunger as a weapon under Mengistu's rule.<ref name="Black Book" /> The Red Terror was carried out in response to what the Derg termed the 'White Terror', a chain of violent events, assassinations, and killings carried out by what it called "[[:en:Petite_bourgeoisie|petty bourgeois]] reactionaries" who desired a reversal of the 1974 revolution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1979/03/21/addis-ababa-emerges-from-a-long-bloody-war/263ac7da-0f96-444c-ab87-03c80bb1632a/|title=Addis Ababa Emerges From a Long, Bloody War|last=Ottaway|first=David B.|date=21 March 1979|work=The Washington Post|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/features/ethiopia-after-the-revolution-vultures-return-to-the-land-of-sheba-19780921|title=Ethiopia After the Revolution: Vultures in the Land of Sheba|last=Katz|first=Donald R.|date=21 September 1978|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=13 December 2017}}</ref>
[[File:Mengistu_Haile_Mariam_3.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mengistu_Haile_Mariam_3.jpg|left|thumb|220x220px|Ethiopian dictator [[:en:Mengistu_Haile_Mariam|Mengistu Haile Mariam]] (in office 1977–1991) was sentenced to death in Ethiopia for [[:en:Qey_Shibir|crimes]] committed during his government. {{As of|2018}}, he lived in exile in [[:en:Zimbabwe|Zimbabwe]].]]
The [[:en:1983–85_famine_in_Ethiopia|1983–85 famine in Ethiopia]] affected around eight million people, resulting in one million dead. Insurrections against Communist rule sprang up, particularly in the northern regions of Eritrea and Tigray. The [[:en:Tigrayan_People's_Liberation_Front|Tigrayan People's Liberation Front]] (TPLF) merged with other ethnically-based opposition movements in 1989, to form the coalition known as the [[:en:Ethiopian_People's_Revolutionary_Democratic_Front|Ethiopian People's Revolutionary Democratic Front]] (EPRDF).<ref>{{cite book|title=A History of Genocide in Africa|last=Stapleton|first=Timothy J.|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2017|isbn=978-1-4408-3052-5|location=|page=163}}</ref>

Concurrently, the Soviet Union began to retreat from building world communism under [[:en:Mikhail_Gorbachev|Mikhail Gorbachev]]'s ''[[:en:Glasnost|glasnost]]'' and ''[[:en:Perestroika|perestroika]]'' policies, marking a dramatic reduction in aid to Ethiopia from Socialist Bloc countries. This resulted in more economic hardship and the collapse of the military in the face of determined onslaughts by guerrilla forces in the north. The collapse of Marxism–Leninism in general, and in [[:en:Eastern_Europe|eastern Europe]] during the [[:en:Revolutions_of_1989|revolutions of 1989]], coincided with the Soviet Union stopping aid to Ethiopia altogether in 1990. The strategic outlook for Mengistu quickly deteriorated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://memory.loc.gov/frd/etsave/et_04_08.html|title=Foreign Policy|last=|first=|date=|website=Library of Congress – American Memory: Remaining Collections.|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://etheses.lse.ac.uk/2110/1/U613342.pdf|title=Restructuring the Soviet–Ethiopian Relationship: A Csse Study in Asymmetric Exchange|last=Crowell Anderson-Jaquest|first=Tommie|date=May 2002|website=London School of Economics and Political Science|access-date=}}</ref>

EPRDF forces advanced on Addis Ababa in May 1991, and the Soviet Union did not intervene to save the government side. Mengistu fled the country and was granted asylum in [[:en:Zimbabwe|Zimbabwe]], where he still resides.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/ethiopians-follow-zimbabwe-events-with-mengistu-in-mind/968413#|title=ADDIS ABABA|last=Tessema|first=Seleshi|date=November 2017|website=Anadolu Agency|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45043811|title=Why a photo of Mengistu has proved so controversial|last=|first=|date=August 2018|website=BBC News|access-date=}}</ref>

In 2006, after a trial that lasted 12 years, Ethiopia's Federal High Court in Addis Ababa found Mengistu guilty of [[:en:Genocides_in_history#Ethiopia|genocide]] ''in absentia''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mengistu found guilty of genocide|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6171429.stm|quote=Ethiopia's Marxist ex-ruler, [[Mengistu Haile Mariam]], has been found guilty of genocide after a 12-year trial.|publisher=BBC|date=12 December 2006|accessdate=21 July 2007}}</ref> Numerous other top leaders of his government were also found guilty of [[:en:War_crime|war crimes]]. Mengistu and others who had fled the country were tried and sentenced ''in absentia''. Numerous former officials received the death sentence and tens of others spent the next 20 years in jail, before being pardoned from life sentences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2005/61569.htm|title=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor 2005|last=|first=|date=March 2006|website=U.S. Department of State|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/mengistu-haile-mariam/|title=Mengistu Haile Mariam|last=|first=|date=June 2006|website=Trial International|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/eshetu-alemu/|title=Eshetu Alemu|last=|first=|date=January 2018|website=Trial International|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ahrlj.up.ac.za/aneme-g-a|title=Apology and trials: The case of the Red Terror trials in Ethiopia|last=Alemu Aneme|first=Girmachew|date=2001|website=African Human Rights Law Journal|access-date=}}</ref>

In July 1991, EPRDF convened a National Conference to establish the [[:en:Transitional_Government_of_Ethiopia|Transitional Government of Ethiopia]] composed of an 87-member Council of Representatives and guided by a national charter that functioned as a transitional constitution.{{sfn|Lyons|1996|pp=121–23}} In June 1992, the [[:en:Oromo_Liberation_Front|Oromo Liberation Front]] withdrew from the government; in March 1993, members of the [[:en:Southern_Ethiopia_Peoples'_Democratic_Coalition|Southern Ethiopia Peoples' Democratic Coalition]] also left the government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/outofdate/bgn/ethiopia/91642.htm|title=Ethiopia (03/08)|last=|first=|date=|website=U.S. Department of the State|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/history?p_p_id=56_INSTANCE_eglYuFCcMdKJ&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_count=1&_56_INSTANCE_eglYuFCcMdKJ_page=6|title=About Ethiopia|last=|first=|date=|website=Ethiopian Government Portal|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023034822/http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/history?p_p_id=56_INSTANCE_eglYuFCcMdKJ&p_p_lifecycle=0&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-1&p_p_col_count=1&_56_INSTANCE_eglYuFCcMdKJ_page=6|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1994, a new constitution was written that established a parliamentary republic with a bicameral legislature and a judicial system.

=== <span id="AnchorFederal">Federal Democratic Republic (1991–present)</span> ===
{{See also|Eritrean independence referendum, 1993}}
[[File:Meles_Zenawi_-_World_Economic_Forum_Annual_Meeting_2012.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Meles_Zenawi_-_World_Economic_Forum_Annual_Meeting_2012.jpg|thumb|Former Prime Minister [[:en:Meles_Zenawi|Meles Zenawi]] at the 2012 [[:en:World_Economic_Forum|World Economic Forum]] annual meeting]]
The [[:en:Ethiopian_general_election,_1995|first multiparty election]] took place in May 1995, which was won by the EPRDF.{{Sfn|Lyons|1996|p=142}} The president of the transitional government, EPRDF leader [[:en:Meles_Zenawi|Meles Zenawi]], became the first [[:en:Prime_Minister_of_Ethiopia|Prime Minister]] of the Federal Democratic Republic of Ethiopia, and [[:en:Negasso_Gidada|Negasso Gidada]] was elected its president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report/22561/ethiopia-president-expelled-ruling-party|title=President expelled from ruling party|date=25 June 2001|work=IRIN|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>

In May 1998, a border dispute with Eritrea led to the [[:en:Eritrean–Ethiopian_War|Eritrean–Ethiopian War]], which lasted until June 2000 and cost both countries an estimated $1&nbsp;million a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/750789.stm|title=Will arms ban slow war?|last=|first=|date=18 May 2000|website=BBC News|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170112074549/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/750789.stm|archive-date=12 January 2017|url-status=live|access-date=12 January 2017|df=}}</ref> This had a negative effect on Ethiopia's economy,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1476618.stm|title=War 'devastated' Ethiopian economy|last=|first=|date=7 August 2001|website=BBC News|publisher=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160704131529/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1476618.stm|archive-date=4 July 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 January 2017|df=}}</ref> but strengthened the ruling coalition.{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}

Ethiopia's [[:en:Ethiopian_general_election,_2005|3rd multiparty election]] on 15 May 2005 was highly disputed, with some opposition groups claiming fraud. Though the [[:en:Carter_Center|Carter Center]] approved the pre-election conditions, it expressed its dissatisfaction with post-election events. [[:en:European_Union|European Union]] election observers cited state support for the EPRDF campaign, as well as irregularities in ballot counting and results publishing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/article-2005-ethiopian-election-a-look-back-93947294/159888.html|title=2005 Ethiopian election: a look back|last=Voice of America|date=16 May 2010|access-date=6 May 2018}}</ref> The opposition parties gained more than 200 parliamentary seats, compared with just 12 in the [[:en:Ethiopian_general_election,_2000|2000 elections]]. While most of the opposition representatives joined the parliament, some leaders of the [[:en:Coalition_for_Unity_and_Democracy|CUD]] party who refused to take up their parliamentary seats were accused of inciting the post-election violence and were imprisoned. [[:en:Amnesty_International|Amnesty International]] considered them "[[:en:Prisoner_of_conscience|prisoners of conscience]]" and they were subsequently released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/afr25/017/2005/en/|title=Document|website=www.amnesty.org|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>

A coalition of [[:en:List_of_political_parties_in_Ethiopia|opposition parties]] and some individuals was established in 2009 to oust the government of the EPRDF in [[:en:Ethiopian_general_election,_2010|legislative elections of 2010]]. Meles' party, which has been in power since 1991, published its 65-page manifesto in Addis Ababa on 10 October 2009. The opposition won most votes in Addis Ababa, but the EPRDF halted counting of votes for several days. After it ensued, it claimed the election, amidst charges of fraud and intimidation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/may/25/ethiopia-election-irregularities-claim|title=Ethiopia election marred by intimidation, say rights group|last=Press|first=Associated|date=25 May 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>
[[File:Ethiopia-FinMin.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ethiopia-FinMin.jpg|left|thumb|The Ministry of Finance and Economic Development headquarters]]
Some of the eight member parties of the [[:en:Medrek|Medrek]] (Forum for Democratic Dialogue) include the [[:en:Oromo_Federalist_Congress|Oromo Federalist Congress]] (organized by the [[:en:Oromo_Federalist_Democratic_Movement|Oromo Federalist Democratic Movement]] and the [[:en:Oromo_People's_Congress|Oromo People's Congress]]), the [[:en:Arena_Tigray|Arena Tigray]] (organized by former members of the ruling party TPLF), the [[:en:Unity_for_Democracy_and_Justice|Unity for Democracy and Justice]] (UDJ, whose leader is imprisoned), and the [[:en:Coalition_of_Somali_Democratic_Forces|Coalition of Somali Democratic Forces]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}

In mid-2011, two consecutively missed rainy seasons precipitated the worst [[:en:2011_East_Africa_drought|drought in East Africa]] seen in 60 years. Full recovery from the drought's effects did not occur until 2012, with long-term strategies by the national government in conjunction with development agencies believed to offer the most sustainable results.<ref name="Twdisyihoa">{{cite web|title=The worst drought in 60 years in Horn Africa|url=http://www.africa-eu-partnership.org/node/2158|publisher=Africa and Europe in Partnership|accessdate=2 August 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102172007/http://www.africa-eu-partnership.org/node/2158|archivedate=2 November 2011}}</ref>
[[File:Deputy_Secretary_of_Defense_Ashton_B._Carter,_left,_is_greeted_by_Ethiopian_Prime_Minister_Hailemariam_Desalegn_at_his_office_in_Addis_Ababa,_Ethiopia,_on_July_24,_2013_130724-M-EV637-339.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Deputy_Secretary_of_Defense_Ashton_B._Carter,_left,_is_greeted_by_Ethiopian_Prime_Minister_Hailemariam_Desalegn_at_his_office_in_Addis_Ababa,_Ethiopia,_on_July_24,_2013_130724-M-EV637-339.jpg|thumb|Former Prime Minister of Ethiopia [[:en:Hailemariam_Desalegn|Hailemariam Desalegn]] meeting with former US Deputy Secretary of Defense [[:en:Ash_Carter|Ash Carter]] in Addis Ababa.]]
Meles died on 20 August 2012 in Brussels, where he was being treated for an unspecified illness.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles has died: state television|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/21/us-ethiopia-meles-idUSBRE87K04K20120821|work=Reuters|date=21 August 2012}}</ref> Deputy Prime Minister [[:en:Hailemariam_Desalegn|Hailemariam Desalegn]] was appointed as a new prime minister until the [[:en:Ethiopian_general_election,_2015|2015 elections]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Ethiopia acting PM to remain at helm until 2015|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/22/us-ethiopia-meles-leader-idUSBRE87L0B820120822|work=Reuters|date=22 August 2012|first=Richard|last=Lough}}</ref> and remained so afterwards with his party in control of every parliamentary seat.<ref name="AJE HD holds">{{Cite web|last=Malone|first=Barry|date=27 May 2015|title=Profile: Ethiopia's 'placeholder' PM quietly holds on|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/05/profile-ethiopias-placeholder-pm-quietly-holds-150527172136197.html|website=aljazeera.com|publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]]|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>

[[:en:2016_Ethiopian_protests|Protests broke out across the country on 5 August 2016]] and dozens of protesters were subsequently shot and killed by police. The protesters demanded an end to human rights abuses, the release of political prisoners, a fairer redistribution of the wealth generated by over a decade of economic growth, and a return of [[:en:Wolqayt|Wolqayt District]] to the [[:en:Amhara_Region|Amhara Region]].<ref name="BBC1">{{cite news|last=|first=|date=7 August 2016|title='Several killed' as Ethiopia police clash with protesters|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-37004725|work=BBC|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="BBC2">{{cite web|last=|first=|date=8 August 2016|title=Internet shutdown ends as protests continue in Ethiopia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/world-africa-36881410|work=BBC Monitoring|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref><ref name="Reuters1">{{cite news|last=Maasho|first=Aaron|date=8 August 2016|title=At least 33 protesters killed in Ethiopia's Oromiya region: opposition|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/topNews/idAFKCN10J0ZJ?sp=true|agency=Reuters|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> The events were the most violent crackdown against protesters in [[:en:Sub-Saharan_Africa|Sub-Saharan Africa]] since the Ethiopian government killed at least 75 people during protests in the [[:en:Oromia_Region|Oromia Region]] in November and December 2015.<ref>{{Citation|title=At least 75 killed in Ethiopia protests|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AYVC7iSR2Qc|language=en|access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Ethiopia Protests {{!}} At Least 140 Killed In Over State Land Plan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HhnLs4kLETk|language=en|access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref> Following these protests, Ethiopia declared a [[:en:Ethiopia_State_of_Emergency_2016|state of emergency]] on 6{{nbsp}}October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.africanews.com/2016/10/09/ethiopia-declares-6-months-state-of-emergency-over-oromia-protests//|title=Ethiopia declares 6 months state of emergency over Oromia protests {{!}} Africanews|last=AfricaNews|work=Africanews|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref> The state of emergency was lifted in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.africanews.com/2017/10/26/deaths-reported-as-ethiopia-elite-forces-clash-with-protesters-in-oromia//|title=10 killed as Ethiopia forces clash with protesters in Oromia|last=AfricaNews|date=26 October 2017|work=Africanews|access-date=7 November 2017}}</ref>

On 16 February 2018, the government of Ethiopia declared a six-month nationwide state of emergency following the resignation of Prime Minister [[:en:Hailemariam_Desalegn|Hailemariam Desalegn]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-43091248|title=Ethiopia declares state of emergency|date=16 February 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref> Hailemariam is the first ruler in modern Ethiopian history to step down; previous leaders have died in office or been overthrown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.france24.com/en/20180306-ethiopia-state-emergency-protest-strike|title=Ethiopians protesting state of emergency shut down capital, Oromia region|date=6 March 2018|publisher=France 24}}</ref> He said he wanted to clear the way for reforms.

=== Government reforms (2018–present) ===
The new Prime Minister was [[:en:Abiy_Ahmed|Abiy Ahmed]], who made a [[:en:2018_Eritrea–Ethiopia_summit|historic visit]] to [[:en:Eritrea|Eritrea]] in 2018, ending the [[:en:Eritrean–Ethiopian_border_conflict|state of conflict between the countries]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-44764597|title=Ethiopia and Eritrea declare end of war|date=9 July 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref> For his efforts in ending the 20-year-long war between Ethiopia and Eritrea [[:en:Abiy_Ahmed|Abiy Ahmed]] was awarded with the Nobel prize for peace in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/videos/world/2019/10/11/ethiopian-prime-minister-abiy-ahmed-wins-2019-nobel-peace-prize-lon-orig.cnn/video/playlists/intl-stories-worth-watching/|title=Ethiopian Prime Minister wins the 2019 Nobel Peace Prize|date=16 October 2019|work=CNN News}}</ref> Since taking office in April 2018, 42-year-old Abiy has also released political prisoners, promised fair elections for 2019 and announced sweeping economic reforms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kaps|first1=Alisa|title=From agrarian country to industrial hub|url=https://www.dandc.eu/en/article/strengthening-foreign-trade-has-helped-ethiopias-governments-achieve-remarkable-economic|website=D+C, Development and cooperation}}</ref> {{As of|2019|06|6|post=,}} all the previously censored websites were made accessible again, over a thousand political prisoners were released and hundreds of administrative staff were fired as part of the reforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://menafn.com/qn_news_story_s.aspx?storyid=1097918154&title=Ethiopia-grants-pardon-to-530-prisoners-before-Christmas-celebrations|title=Ethiopia grants pardon to 530 prisoners before Christmas celebrations|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ooni.torproject.org/post/ethiopia-unblocking/|title=OONI – Ethiopia: Verifying the unblocking of websites|website=ooni.torproject.org|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newbusinessethiopia.com/ethiopia-prison-administration-fires-103-individuals/|title=Ethiopia prison administration fires 103 individuals – New Business Ethiopia|language=en-US|access-date=14 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113175528/https://newbusinessethiopia.com/ethiopia-prison-administration-fires-103-individuals/|archive-date=13 January 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cyberethiopia.com/2013/?p=2012|title=Reflections on the Rule of Law and Ethiopia's Transition to Democratic Rule (Part I)|date=12 January 2019|website=Cyber Ethiopia|language=en-US|access-date=14 January 2019}}</ref>

[[:en:Human_Rights_in_Ethiopia#Ethnic_violence|Ethnic violence rose]] with the political unrest. There were [[:en:Oromo–Somali_clashes|Oromo–Somali clashes]] between the Oromo, who make up the largest ethnic group in the country, and the ethnic Somalis, leading to up to 400,000 have been displaced in 2017.<ref name="irinnews">{{cite news|url=http://www.irinnews.org/analysis/2017/11/08/ethnic-violence-displaces-hundreds-thousands-ethiopians|title=Ethnic violence displaces hundreds of thousands of Ethiopians|publisher=irinnews.com|date=8 November 2017}}</ref> [[:en:Gedeo–Oromo_clashes|Gedeo–Oromo clashes]] between the Oromo and the [[:en:Gedeo_people|Gedeo people]] in the south of the country led to Ethiopia having the largest number of people to flee their homes in the world in 2018, with 1.4&nbsp;million newly displaced people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/ethiopia/ethiopia-tops-global-list-highest-internal-displacement-2018|title=Ethiopia tops global list of highest internal displacement in 2018|publisher=Relief Web|accessdate=7 April 2019}}</ref> In September 2018 in the minorities protest that took place in Oromo near the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa, 23 people were killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/World/2018/Sep-17/463632-at-least-23-die-in-weekend-of-ethiopia-ethnic-violence.ashx|title=At least 23 die in weekend of Ethiopia ethnic violence|date=17 September 2018}}</ref> Some have blamed the rise in ethnic violence by the Oromo on the new Oromo Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed for giving space to groups formerly banned by previous [[:en:Tigrayans|Tigrayan]]-led governments, such as the [[:en:Oromo_Liberation_Front|Oromo Liberation Front]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/09/24/world/africa/ethiopia-ethnic-violence-arrests.html|title=Thousands Are Arrested in Ethiopia After Ethnic Violence|date=24 September 2018|accessdate=27 April 2019}}</ref>

== Politics ==
{{Main|Politics of Ethiopia}}<!--Please add new information to relevant articles of the series, not here-->{{see also|Rulers and Heads of State of Ethiopia|Foreign relations of Ethiopia|Ethiopian National Defense Force|2016 Ethiopian protests}}The politics of Ethiopia takes place in a framework of a [[:en:Federalism|federal]] [[:en:Parliamentary_republic|parliamentary republic]], wherein the [[:en:Prime_Minister_of_Ethiopia|Prime Minister]] is the [[:en:Head_of_government|head of government]].

The [[:en:President_of_Ethiopia|President]] is the [[:en:Head_of_state|head of state]] but with largely ceremonial powers. [[:en:Executive_power|Executive power]] is exercised by the government. Federal [[:en:Legislative_power|legislative power]] is vested in both the government and the two chambers of parliament. On the basis of Article 78 of the 1994 Ethiopian Constitution, the [[:en:Judiciary|Judiciary]] is completely independent of the executive and the legislature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.civicwebs.com/cwvlib/constitutions/ethiopia/constitution_1994.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509194433/http://www.civicwebs.com/cwvlib/constitutions/ethiopia/constitution_1994.htm|url-status=dead|title=Constitution of Ethiopia – 8 December 1994|archivedate=9 May 2008}}</ref> In 2015, the realities of this provision were questioned in a report prepared by [[:en:Freedom_House|Freedom House]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2015/ethiopia|title=Ethiopia {{!}} Country report {{!}} Freedom in the World {{!}} 2015|last=|first=|date=21 January 2015|website=freedomhouse.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118081031/https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/2015/ethiopia|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=live|access-date=8 January 2017}}</ref>
