=== Wildlife ===
{{Main|Wildlife of Ethiopia}}
[[File:Canis_simensis_-Simien_Mountains,_Ethiopia-8.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Canis_simensis_-Simien_Mountains,_Ethiopia-8.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Ethiopian_wolf|Ethiopian wolf]]]]
Ethiopia has 31 endemic species of mammals.<ref name="Massicot">Massicot, Paul (2005). [http://www.animalinfo.org/country/ethiopia.htm Animal Info-Ethiopia].</ref> The [[:en:African_wild_dog|African wild dog]] prehistorically had widespread distribution in the territory. However, with last sightings at [[:en:Finicha'a|Finicha'a]], this canid is thought to be potentially [[:en:Local_extinction|locally extinct]]. The Ethiopian wolf is perhaps the most researched of all the endangered species within Ethiopia.

Ethiopia is a global center of avian diversity. To date more than 856 bird species have been recorded in Ethiopia, twenty of which are endemic to the country.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lepage|first=Denis|title=Bird Checklists of the World|url=http://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/checklist.jsp?region=et&list=clements|publisher=Avibase|accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref> Sixteen species are endangered or critically endangered. Many of these birds feed on butterflies, like the ''[[:en:Bicyclus_anynana|Bicyclus anynana]].''<ref>Bicyclus, Site of Markku Savela</ref>
[[File:Ethiopian_Butterfly_(2377703189).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ethiopian_Butterfly_(2377703189).jpg|left|thumb|A [[:en:Swallowtail_butterfly|Swallowtail butterfly]] at [[:en:Lake_Tana|Lake Tana]]]]
Historically, throughout the African continent, [[:en:Wildlife|wildlife]] populations have been rapidly declining due to logging, civil wars, pollution, poaching, and other human factors.<ref>Bakerova, Katarina et al. (1991) Wildlife Parks Animals Africa. Retrieved 24 May 2008, from the [http://www.africanculturalcenter.org/3_0wildlife.html African Cultural Center] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110205045029/http://www.africanculturalcenter.org/3_0wildlife.html|date=5 February 2011}}.</ref> A 17-year-long civil war, along with severe drought, negatively affected Ethiopia's environmental conditions, leading to even greater habitat degradation.<ref>Encyclopedia of Nations. [http://www.nationsencyclopedia.com/Africa/Ethiopia-ENVIRONMENT.html Ethiopia Environment].</ref> Habitat destruction is a factor that leads to endangerment. When changes to a habitat occur rapidly, animals do not have time to adjust. Human impact threatens many species, with greater threats expected as a result of climate change induced by [[:en:Greenhouse_gas|greenhouse gases]].<ref>Kurpis, Lauren (2002). [http://www.endangeredspecie.com/Ways_To_Help.htm How to Help Endangered Species] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304003612/http://www.endangeredspecie.com/Ways_To_Help.htm|date=4 March 2011}}. Endageredspecie.com</ref> With carbon dioxide emissions in 2010 of 6,494,000 tonnes, Ethiopia contributes just 0.02% to the annual human-caused release of greenhouse gases.<ref>United Nations Statistics Division, [http://mdgs.un.org/unsd/mdg/SeriesDetail.aspx?srid=749&crid= Millennium Development Goals indicators]: Carbon dioxide emissions (CO2), thousand tonnes of CO2 (collected by CDIAC) Human-produced, direct emissions of carbon dioxide only. Excludes other greenhouse gases; [[land use, land-use change, and forestry]] (LULUCF); and natural background flows of CO2 (See also: Carbon cycle)</ref>

Ethiopia has many species listed as critically endangered, endangered, and vulnerable to global extinction. The threatened species in Ethiopia can be broken down into three categories (based on [[:en:IUCN|IUCN]] ratings): [[:en:Critically_endangered|critically endangered]], [[:en:Endangered_species|endangered]], and [[:en:Vulnerable_species|vulnerable]].<ref name="Massicot" />{{Clear left}}
