The country's population is highly diverse, containing over 80 different ethnic groups. According to the Ethiopian national census of 2007, the [[:en:Oromo_people|Oromo]] are the largest ethnic group in Ethiopia, at 34.4% of the nation's population. The [[:en:Amhara_people|Amhara]] represent 27.0% of the country's inhabitants, while [[:en:Somalis|Somalis]] and [[:en:Tigrayans|Tigrayans]] represent 6.2% and 6.1% of the population, respectively. Other prominent ethnic groups are as follows: [[:en:Sidama_people|Sidama]] 4.0%, [[:en:Gurage_people|Gurage]] 2.5%, [[:en:Welayta_people|Welayta]] 2.3%, [[:en:Afar_people|Afar]] 1.7%, [[:en:Hadiya_people|Hadiya]] 1.7%, [[:en:Gamo_people|Gamo]] 1.5% and [[:en:List_of_ethnic_groups_in_Ethiopia|Arabs and others]] 12.6%.

[[:en:Afroasiatic_languages|Afroasiatic-speaking]] communities make up the majority of the population. Among these, Semitic speakers often collectively refer to themselves as the [[:en:Habesha_people|Habesha people]]. The [[:en:Arabic|Arabic]] form of this term (''al-Ḥabasha'') is the etymological basis of "Abyssinia," the former name of Ethiopia in English and other European languages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.time.com/time/europe/timetrails/selassie/hs260809.html|title=Time Europe&nbsp;– Abyssinia: Ethiopian Protest|accessdate=5 June 2005|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040206124546/http://www.time.com/time/europe/timetrails/selassie/hs260809.html|archivedate=6 February 2004}}. 9{{nbsp}}August 1926</ref> Additionally, [[:en:Nilo-Saharan_languages|Nilo-Saharan-speaking]] ethnic minorities inhabit the southern regions of the country, particularly in areas of the [[:en:Gambela_Region|Gambela Region]] which borders [[:en:South_Sudan|South Sudan]]. The largest ethnic groups among these include the [[:en:Nuer_people|Nuer]] and [[:en:Anuak_people|Anuak]].

In addition, Ethiopia had over 75,000 [[:en:Italians_of_Ethiopia|Italian settlers]] during the Italian occupation of the country.<ref name="Istat 2010">{{cite journal|last=[[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]]|title=I censimenti nell'Italia unita I censimenti nell'Italia unita Le fonti di stato della popolazione tra il XIX e il XXI secolo ISTITUTO NAZIONALE DI STATISTICA SOCIETÀ ITALIANA DI DEMOGRAFIA STORICA Le fonti di stato della popolazione tra il XIX e il XXI secolo|journal=Annali di Statistica|date=December 2010|volume=2|series=XII|page=263|url=http://www3.istat.it/dati/catalogo/20120911_00/Annali_serie_XII_vol_2_anno_141_I_Censimenti_nell'Italia_unita_bis.pdf|accessdate=24 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803195051/http://www3.istat.it/dati/catalogo/20120911_00/Annali_serie_XII_vol_2_anno_141_I_Censimenti_nell'Italia_unita_bis.pdf|archive-date=3 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> After independence, many Italians remained for decades after receiving full pardons from Emperor Selassie, as he saw the opportunity to continue modernization efforts.<ref name="Italoethiopians">{{Cite web|url=https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211022551/https://ladywriteronline.wordpress.com/2008/04/29/fratelli-detiopia/|url-status=dead|title=Fratelli d'Etiopia|date=29 April 2008|archivedate=11 February 2017}}</ref> However, due to the [[:en:Ethiopian_Civil_War|Ethiopian Civil War]] in 1974, nearly 22,000 Italo-Ethiopians left the country.<ref name="Italoethiopians" /> In the 2000s, some Italian companies returned to operate in Ethiopia, and many Italian technicians and managers arrived with their families, residing mainly in the metropolitan area of the capital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dait.interno.gov.it/servizi-demografici|title=I servizi demografici|date=25 November 2016|website=Dipartimento per gli affari interni e territoriali}}</ref>

In 2009, Ethiopia hosted a population of refugees and asylum seekers numbering approximately 135,200. The majority of this population came from Somalia (approximately 64,300 persons), Eritrea (41,700) and Sudan (25,900). The Ethiopian government required nearly all refugees to live in refugee camps.<ref name="World Refugee Survey 2009">{{cite news|title=World Refugee Survey 2008|publisher=U.S. Committee for Refugees and Immigrants|date=19 June 2008|url=http://www.refugees.org/resources/refugee-warehousing/archived-world-refugee-surveys/2009-wrs-country-updates/ethiopia.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502073801/http://www.refugees.org/resources/refugee-warehousing/archived-world-refugee-surveys/2009-wrs-country-updates/ethiopia.html|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=}}</ref>

=== Languages ===
{{Main|Languages of Ethiopia}}{{Pie chart|thumb=right|label9=[[Hadiyya language|Hadiyya]]|label7=[[Gurage languages|Gurage]]|value7=2.0|color7=Brown|label8=[[Afar language|Afar]]|value8=1.7|color8=Orange|value9=1.7|value6=2.2|color9=Teal|label10=[[Gamo-Gofa-Dawro language|Gamo-Gofa-Dawro]]|value10=1.5|color10=Gray|label11=[[Languages of Ethiopia#Overview|others]]|value11=11.6|color6=Black|label6=[[Wolaytta language|Wolaytta]]|caption=[[Languages of Ethiopia]] {{As of|2007|lc=y}} Census<ref name=2007Census />|label3=[[Somali language|Somali]]|label1=[[Oromo language|Oromo]]|value1=33.8|color1=Green|label2=[[Amharic]]|value2=29.3|color2=Yellow|value3=6.3|color5=Purple|color3=Red|label4=[[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]]|value4=5.9|color4=Blue|label5=[[Sidamo language|Sidamo]]|value5=4.0|color11=white}}According to ''[[:en:Ethnologue|Ethnologue]]'', there are 90 individual languages spoken in Ethiopia.<ref name="Ethnologue">{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/country/ET|title=Languages of Ethiopia|publisher=SIL International|archive-url=https://archive.today/20170318194709/https://www.ethnologue.com/country/ET|archive-date=18 March 2017|url-status=live|work=Ethnologue|accessdate=9 February 2013}}</ref> Most people in the country speak [[:en:Afroasiatic_languages|Afroasiatic languages]] of the [[:en:Cushitic_languages|Cushitic]] or [[:en:Semitic_languages|Semitic]] branches. The former includes [[:en:Oromo_language|Oromo language]], spoken by the [[:en:Oromo_people|Oromo]], and [[:en:Somali_language|Somali]], spoken by the [[:en:Somalis|Somalis]]; the latter includes [[:en:Amharic|Amharic]], spoken by the [[:en:Amhara_people|Amhara]], and [[:en:Tigrinya_language|Tigrinya]], spoken by the [[:en:Tigrayans|Tigrayans]]. Together, these four groups make up about three-quarters of Ethiopia's population. Other Afroasiatic languages with a significant number of speakers include the Cushitic [[:en:Sidamo_language|Sidamo]], [[:en:Afar_language|Afar]], [[:en:Hadiyya_language|Hadiyya]] and [[:en:Agaw_languages|Agaw languages]], as well as the Semitic [[:en:Gurage_languages|Gurage languages]], [[:en:Harari_language|Harari]], [[:en:Silt'e_language|Silt'e]], and [[:en:Argobba_language|Argobba]] languages. [[:en:Arabic|Arabic]], which also belongs to the Afroasiatic family, is likewise spoken in some areas.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Yigezu|first1=Moges|title=Language Ideologies and Challenges of Multilingual Education in Ethiopia|date=2012|publisher=African Books Collective|isbn=978-99944-55-47-8|page=143|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=2Is2nUM-5UQC&pg=PA143}}</ref>

Additionally, [[:en:Omotic_languages|Omotic languages]] are spoken by Omotic ethnic minority groups inhabiting the southern regions. Among these idioms are [[:en:Aari_language|Aari]], [[:en:Bench_language|Bench]], [[:en:Dime_language|Dime]], [[:en:Dizin_language|Dizin]], [[:en:Gamo-Gofa-Dawro_language|Gamo-Gofa-Dawro]], [[:en:Maale_language|Maale]], [[:en:Hamer_language|Hamer]], and [[:en:Wolaytta_language|Wolaytta]].

Languages from the [[:en:Nilo-Saharan_languages|Nilo-Saharan family]] are also spoken by ethnic minorities concentrated in the southwestern parts of the country. These languages include [[:en:Nuer_language|Nuer]], [[:en:Anuak_language|Anuak]], [[:en:Nyangatom_language|Nyangatom]], [[:en:Majang_language|Majang]], [[:en:Suri_language|Suri]], [[:en:Me'en_language|Me'en]], and [[:en:Mursi_language|Mursi]].

English is the most widely spoken foreign language, and is the medium of instruction in secondary schools. Amharic was the language of primary school instruction, but has been replaced in many areas by regional languages such as Oromiffa, Somali or Tigrinya.<ref name="Llicuv">{{cite book|editor1=Mpoche, Kizitus|editor2=Mbuh, Tennu|title=Language, literature, and identity|year=2006|publisher=Cuvillier|isbn=978-3-86537-839-2|pages=163–64|url=https://books.google.com/?id=PNEiAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> While all languages enjoy equal state recognition in the [[:en:1995_Constitution_of_Ethiopia|1995 Constitution of Ethiopia]] and [[:en:Oromo_language|Oromo]] is the most widely spoken language, Amharic is recognized as the official [[:en:Working_language|working language]] of the [[:en:Government_of_Ethiopia|Federal Government]].

The various [[:en:Regions_of_Ethiopia|regions of Ethiopia]] and [[:en:Charter_city|chartered cities]] are free to determine their own working languages.<ref name="Llicuv" /> Amharic is recognised as the official working language of [[:en:Amhara_Region|Amhara Region]], [[:en:Benishangul-Gumuz|Benishangul-Gumuz]], [[:en:Southern_Nations,_Nationalities,_and_Peoples'_Region|Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region]], [[:en:Gambela_Region|Gambela Region]], [[:en:Addis_Abeba|Addis Abeba]] and [[:en:Dire_Dawa|Dire Dawa]].<ref>Gebremichael, M. (2011). ''Federalism and conflict management in Ethiopia: case study of Benishangul-Gumuz Regional State''. PhD Thesis. United Kingdom: University of Bradford.</ref> [[:en:Oromo_language|Oromo language]] serves as the official working language and the primary language of education in the Oromia,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/et.html|title=The world factbook|website=cia.gov}}</ref> [[:en:Harar|Harar]] and [[:en:Dire_Dawa|Dire Dawa]] and of the [[:en:Oromia_Zone|Oromia Zone]] in the [[:en:Amhara_Region|Amhara Region]]. Somali is the official working language of [[:en:Somali_region|Somali region]] and [[:en:Dire_Dawa|Dire Dawa]], while Afar,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/afar-regional-state|title=Afar Regional State|website=Government of Ethiopia|access-date=27 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728193815/http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/afar-regional-state|archive-date=28 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Harari,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/harari-regional-state|title=Harari Regional State|website=Government of Ethiopia|access-date=27 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728191721/http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/harari-regional-state|archive-date=28 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and Tigrinya<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/tigray-regional-state|title=Tigray Regional State|website=Government of Ethiopia|access-date=27 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727163310/http://www.ethiopia.gov.et/tigray-regional-state|archive-date=27 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> are recognized as official working languages in their respective regions.

[[:en:Italian_language|Italian]] is still spoken by few parts of the population, mostly among older generations, and is taught in many schools (most notably the [[:en:Istituto_Statale_Italiano_Omnicomprensivo_di_Addis_Abeba|Istituto Statale Italiano Omnicomprensivo di Addis Abeba]]). Also, Amharic and Tigrinya have many words borrowed from the Italian language.<ref name="Yaqob">{{cite web|url=https://totalitarismo.altervista.org/italianismi-nel-somalo-e-nell-amarico/|title=Italianismi nel somalo e nell'amarico|first=Mister|last=Totalitarismo|date=2 December 2018}}</ref><ref name="altervista">''I prestiti italiani in amarico e tigrino'', Yaqob Beyene</ref>

=== Script ===
Ethiopia's principal orthography is the [[:en:Ge'ez_script|Ge'ez script]]. Employed as an [[:en:Abugida|abugida]] for several of the country's languages, it first came into usage in the 6th and 5th centuries BC as an [[:en:Abjad|abjad]] to transcribe the Semitic [[:en:Ge'ez_language|Ge'ez language]].<ref>Fattovich, Rodolfo (2003) "Akkälä Guzay" in von Uhlig, Siegbert, ed. ''Encyclopaedia Aethiopica: A-C''. Weissbaden: Otto Harrassowitz KG, p.169.</ref> Ge'ez now serves as the liturgical language of both the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo]] and [[:en:Eritrean_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Eritrean Orthodox Tewahedo]] Churches. During the 1980s, the Ethiopic character set was computerized. It is today part of the [[:en:Unicode|Unicode]] standard as Ethiopic, [[:en:Ethiopic_Extended|Ethiopic Extended]], [[:en:Ethiopic_Supplement|Ethiopic Supplement]] and [[:en:Ethiopic_Extended-A|Ethiopic Extended-A]].

Other [[:en:Writing_system|writing systems]] have also been used over the years by different Ethiopian communities. The latter include [[:en:Bakri_Sapalo|Bakri Sapalo]]'s script for Oromiffa.<ref name="HH-551">{{Cite journal|doi=10.1017/S0041977X00144209|jstor=616613|title=The Oromo orthography of Shaykh Bakri Saṗalō|journal=Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies|volume=44|issue=3|pages=550|year=2009|last1=Hayward|first1=R.J.|last2=Hassan|first2=M.}}</ref>

=== Religion ===
{{Main|Religion in Ethiopia}}<!--These data were checked for 2007 National Census in ref provided below. Do not alter or falsify the reference. This section is being watched carefully.-->{{Pie chart|thumb=right|label4=[[Traditional African religions|Traditional faiths]]|value6=0.7|label6=[[Beta Israel|Judaism]]|color5=DarkBlue|value5=0.7|label5=[[Catholic Church in Ethiopia|Catholicism]]|color54=GreenYellow|value4=2.6|color3=DodgerBlue|caption=[[Religion in Ethiopia]] (2007)|value3=18.6|label3=[[P'ent'ay]]/[[Protestantism in Ethiopia|Protestantism]]|color2=Green|value2=33.9|label2=[[Islam in Ethiopia|Islam]]|color1=Orchid|value1=43.5|label1=[[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church|Ethiopian Orthodox]]|color6=Red}}Ethiopia has close historical ties with all three of the world's major [[:en:Abrahamic_religions|Abrahamic religions]]. In the 4th century, the Ethiopian empire was one of the first in the world to officially adopt [[:en:Christianity|Christianity]] as the state religion. As a result of the resolutions of the Council of Chalcedon, in 451 the [[:en:Miaphysitism|miaphysites]],<ref name="first seven">{{cite book|last=Davis, [[Society of Jesus|SJ]]|first=Leo Donald|title=The First Seven Ecumenical Councils (325–787): Their History and Theology (Theology and Life Series 21)|year=1990|publisher=Michael Glazier/Liturgical Press|location=Collegeville, MN|isbn=978-0-8146-5616-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/firstsevenec_davi_1990_000_6702418/page/342 342]|url=https://archive.org/details/firstsevenec_davi_1990_000_6702418/page/342}}</ref> which included the vast majority of Christians in Egypt and Ethiopia, were accused of [[:en:Monophysitism|monophysitism]] and designated as heretics under the common name of [[:en:Coptic_Orthodox_Church_of_Alexandria|Coptic Christianity]] (see [[:en:Oriental_Orthodoxy|Oriental Orthodoxy]]). While no longer distinguished as a state religion, the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] remains the majority [[:en:Christian_denomination|Christian denomination]]. There is also a substantial [[:en:Muslims|Muslims]] demographic, representing around a third of the population. Additionally, Ethiopia is the site of the [[:en:First_Hegira|First Hegira]], a major emigration in Islamic history. A town in the [[:en:Tigray_Region|Tigray Region]], [[:en:Negash|Negash]] is the oldest Muslim settlement in Africa.

Until the 1980s, a substantial population of [[:en:Beta_Israel|Beta Israel]] (Ethiopian Jews) resided in Ethiopia.<ref name="Ofcansky">{{cite book|last=Thomas P. Ofcansky|first=LaVerle Berry|title=Ethiopia: A Country Study|year=2004|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|isbn=978-1-4191-1857-9|pages=130–41|url=https://books.google.com/?id=R3M0V0VfgiMC}}</ref><ref>Weil, Shalva (2008) "Zionism among Ethiopian Jews" in ''Jewish Communities in the 19th and 20th Centuries''. Salamon, Hagar (ed.). Ethiopia, Jerusalem: Ben-Zvi Institute, pp. 187–200. (Hebrew).</ref> About 4,000 are estimated to still live in the country, along with many more members of two related ethno-religious groups, the [[:en:Falash_Mura|Falash Mura]] and the [[:en:Beta_Abraham|Beta Abraham]]. The Falash Mura are Beta Israel who, while identifying as Jews, adopted elements of Christianity due to missionary efforts, and now practice a [[:en:Syncretism|syncretic]] form of Ethiopian Judaism mixed with Christianity; they number about 150,000 people. The Beta Abraham are regarded as a medieval offshoot of the Beta Israel, having incorporated elements of [[:en:Traditional_African_religion|traditional African religion]], and number about 8,000. While both still identify as Beta Israel, they exist outside the main community. The official Beta Israel community leaders tentatively accept the Falash Mura, and have requested they be allowed to emigrate to Israel. The Beta Abraham have historically been shunned by most other communities, having a reputation of being "sorcerers".
[[File:Lalibela,_san_giorgio,_esterno_24.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Lalibela,_san_giorgio,_esterno_24.jpg|left|thumb|The rock-hewn [[:en:Church_of_Saint_George,_Lalibela|Church of Saint George, Lalibela]] is a [[:en:World_Heritage_Site|UNESCO World Heritage Site]].]]
According to the 2007 National Census, Christians make up 62.8% of the country's population (43.5% Ethiopian Orthodox, 19.3% other denominations), Muslims 33.9%, practitioners of traditional faiths 2.6%, and other religions 0.6%. This is in agreement with the CIA World Factbook, which states that Christianity is the most widely practiced religion in Ethiopia.<ref name="CIA" /> The ratio of the Christian to Muslim population has largely remained stable when compared to previous censuses conducted decades ago.<ref name="bx">{{Cite web|last=Abegaz|first=Berhanu|date=1 June 2005|title=Ethiopia: A Model Nation of Minorities|url=http://bxabeg.people.wm.edu/Ethiopia.Census%20Portrait.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=|access-date=27 July 2017|via=}}</ref> Sunnis form the majority of Muslims with [[:en:Non-denominational_Muslim|non-denominational Muslims]] being the second largest group of Muslims, and [[:en:Shia_Islam|the Shia]] and [[:en:Ahmadiyya|Ahmadiyyas]] are a minority. Sunnis are largely [[:en:Shafi'i|Shafi'is]] or [[:en:Salafi_movement|Salafis]], and there are also many [[:en:Sufism|Sufi]] Muslims there.<ref>Pew Forum on Religious & Public life. 9{{nbsp}}August 2012. Retrieved 29 October 2013</ref> The large Muslim population in the northern Afar region has resulted in a Muslim separatist movement called the "Islamic State of Afaria" seeking a [[:en:Sharia|sharia]]-compliant constitution.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Islam and nationalism: Two trends of the separatist movement in Ethiopia|journal=Northeast African Studies|first=Alexander|last=Krylov|volume=12|issue=2/3|pages=171–76|year=1990|jstor=43660322}}</ref>

Some critics asserted that the Haile Selassie regime had been fabricating the census to present Ethiopia as a Christian country to the outside world, stating that Islam made up 50% of the total population in 1991, based on the 1984 census commissioned by the [[:en:Derg|Derg]] regime.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Levtzion|first1=Nehemia|authorlink=Nehemia Levtzion|title=The History of Islam in Africa|date=31 March 2000|publisher=Ohio University Press|pages=240–241|isbn=9780821444610|url=https://books.google.com/?id=J1Ipt5A9mLMC&pg=PA240&lpg=PA240&dq=Haile+selassie%27s+regime+which+had+presented+Ethiopia+abroad+as+a+christian+country,+had+carefully+kepy+two+secrets#v=onepage}}</ref> Several Muslim observers and bloggers claim that Muslims are in the majority and disagree with the above census numbers, without providing factual data supporting their claims.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Prunier|first1=Gérard|title=Understanding Contemporary Ethiopia: Monarchy, Revolution and the Legacy of Meles Zenawi|date=15 September 2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9781849046183|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wnxeCwAAQBAJ&pg=PT100&dq=muslims+could+make+up+majority+ethiopia#v=onepage}}</ref>

The [[:en:Kingdom_of_Aksum|Kingdom of Aksum]] was one of the first polities to officially embrace [[:en:Christianity|Christianity]], when [[:en:Frumentius|Frumentius]] of [[:en:Tyre,_Lebanon|Tyre]], called Fremnatos or Abba Selama ("Father of Peace") in Ethiopia, converted Emperor [[:en:Ezana_of_Axum|Ezana]] during the fourth century.<ref name="isbn0-313-32273-2" /><ref name="Ofcansky" /> According to the [[:en:New_Testament|New Testament]], Christianity had entered Ethiopia even earlier, when an official in the Ethiopian royal treasury was baptized by [[:en:Philip_the_Evangelist|Philip the Evangelist]].<ref>[https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts+8 "Acts 8"]. ''Bible Gateway''.</ref>
[[File:01_-_Priests_dancing_for_Timkat.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:01_-_Priests_dancing_for_Timkat.jpg|thumb|Orthodox priests dancing during the celebration of ''[[:en:Timkat|Timkat]]'']]
The [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox_Tewahedo_Church|Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] is part of [[:en:Oriental_Orthodoxy|Oriental Orthodoxy]]. It is by far the largest Christian denomination, although a number of [[:en:P'ent'ay|P'ent'ay]] ([[:en:Protestantism|Protestant]]) churches have recently gained ground. Since 1930, a relatively small [[:en:Ethiopian_Catholic_Church|Ethiopian Catholic Church]] has existed in [[:en:Full_communion|full communion]] with Rome, with adherents making up less than 1% of the total population.<ref name="bx" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/ejhist.html|title=The History of Ethiopian Jews|publisher=Jewishvirtuallibrary.org|accessdate=16 March 2009}}</ref>
[[File:Mešita_v_Bahir_Daru.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Me%C5%A1ita_v_Bahir_Daru.jpg|thumb|A [[:en:Mosque|mosque]] in [[:en:Bahir_Dar|Bahir Dar]]]]
[[:en:Islam_in_Ethiopia|Islam in Ethiopia]] dates back to the founding of the religion in 622 when a group of Muslims were counseled by [[:en:Muhammad|Muhammad]] to escape persecution in [[:en:Mecca|Mecca]]. The disciples subsequently [[:en:Migrated_to_Abyssinia|migrated to Abyssinia]] via modern-day Eritrea, which was at the time ruled by [[:en:Ashama_ibn-Abjar|Ashama ibn-Abjar]], a pious Christian emperor.<ref name="Ofcansky" /> Also, the largest single ethnic group of [[:en:List_of_non-Arab_Sahabah|non-Arab Sahabah]] was that of the Ethiopians.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}

According to the 2007 Population and Housing Census, around 1,957,944 people in Ethiopia are adherents of [[:en:Traditional_African_religion|traditional religions]]. An additional 471,861 residents practice other creeds. While followers of all religions can be found in each region, they tend to be concentrated in certain parts of the country. Christians predominantly live in the northern Amhara and Tigray regions, and are largely members of the non-Chalcedonian Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church. Those belonging to P'ent'ay are centered in the Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region (SNNP) and Oromia. Muslims in Ethiopia predominantly adhere to [[:en:Sunni_Islam|Sunni Islam]] and generally inhabit eastern and northeastern areas; particularly the Somali, Afar, Dire Dawa and Harari regions. Practitioners of traditional religions mainly reside in the nation's far southwestern and western rural borderlands, in the SNNP, Benishangul-Gumuz and Gambela regions.<ref name="Ofcansky" />

[[:en:Human_rights_group|Human rights groups]] have regularly accused the government of arresting activists, journalists and bloggers to stamp out dissent among some religious communities. Lengthy prison terms were handed to 17 Muslim activists on 3{{nbsp}}August 2015 ranging from seven to 22 years. They were charged with trying to create an Islamic state in the majority Christian country. All the defendants denied the charges and claimed that they were merely protesting in defence of their rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailysabah.com/africa/2015/08/04/ethiopia-hands-lengthy-prison-terms-to-muslim-activists|title=Ethiopia hands lengthy prison terms to Muslim activists|date=4 August 2015|work=DailySabah|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/08/03/us-ethiopia-arrests-idUSKCN0Q82AC20150803|title=Ethiopia hands lengthy prison terms to Muslim activists|newspaper=Reuters|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=3 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-33759946|title=Ethiopia jails Muslims convicted of terror plot|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=24 October 2015|date=3 August 2015}}</ref>

==== Beta Israel ====
{{Main|Beta Israel}}{{unreferenced section|date=January 2019}}There is a small, yet significant number of [[:en:Judaism|Jews]] in Ethiopia, who claim to be one of the [[:en:Lost_tribes_of_Israel|lost tribes of Israel]]. In the 1980s, the number of [[:en:Beta_Israel|Ethiopian-Jews]] decreased, as many started moving to [[:en:Israel|Israel]]. The tribe has been given the name [[:en:Beta_Israel|Beta Israel]] / ቤታ እስራኤል / ביתא ישראל. There are a higher number of [[:en:Ethiopian_Jews_in_Israel|Ethiopian-Jews]] living in Israel today, though, in certain Ethiopian towns and villages such as [[:en:Wolleka|Wolleka]], near the Ethiopian city of [[:en:Gondar|Gondar]], the concentration of Ethiopian-Jews reaches an estimated 100%. The US also has a significant number of Ethiopian-Jews, with a population slightly less than that of Ethiopia.

=== Urbanization ===
{{Main|List of cities and towns in Ethiopia}}
[[File:Addis_Abeba07_(Sam_Effron).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Addis_Abeba07_(Sam_Effron).jpg|thumb|Street in Addis Abeba]]
Population growth, migration, and urbanization are all straining both governments' and ecosystems' capacity to provide people with basic services.<ref>Racin, L. (4 March 2008) [http://www.wilsoncenter.org/event/future-shock-how-environmental-change-and-human-impact-are-changing-the-global-map "Future Shock: How Environmental Change and Human Impact Are Changing the Global Map"]. Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars.</ref> Urbanization has steadily been increasing in Ethiopia, with two periods of significantly rapid growth. First, in 1936–1941 during the Italian occupation under Mussolini's fascist government, and from 1967 to 1975 when the populations of urban centers tripled.<ref name="countrystudies1991">Ofcansky, T and Berry, L. "Ethiopia: A Country Study". Edited by Washington: GPO for the Library of Congress, 1991. [http://countrystudies.us/ethiopia Countrystudies.us]</ref>

In 1936, Italy annexed Ethiopia, building infrastructure to connect major cities, and a dam providing power and water.<ref name="Accessed 15 May 2008">Shivley, K. "Addis Ababa, Ethiopia" [http://www.macalester.edu/courses/geog61/kshively/index.html Macalester.edu]. Retrieved 15 May 2008.</ref> This along with the influx of Italians and labourers was the major cause of rapid growth during this period. The second period of growth was from 1967 to 1975 when rural populations migrated to urban centers seeking work and better living conditions.<ref name="countrystudies1991" />

This pattern slowed due to the 1975 Land Reform program instituted by the government, which provided incentives for people to stay in rural areas. As people moved from rural areas to the cities, there were fewer people to grow food for the population. The Land Reform Act was meant to increase agriculture since food production was not keeping up with population growth over the period of 1970–1983. This program proliferated the formation of peasant associations, large villages based on agriculture. The act did lead to an increase in food production, although there is debate over the cause; it may be related to weather conditions more than the reform act.<ref name="Anderson, Frank 1991. Pages 159-175">{{Cite journal|doi=10.1016/0169-5150(91)90022-D|title=Development of agriculture in Ethiopia since the 1975 land reform|journal=Agricultural Economics|volume=6|issue=2|pages=159–75|year=1991|last1=Belete|first1=A.}}</ref> Urban populations have continued to grow with an 8.1% increase from 1975 to 2000.<ref name="Accessed 5-10-08">[http://worldbank.org Worldbank.org]. Retrieved 5 October 2008 {{nonspecific|date=November 2010}}</ref>
