== Education ==
{{Main|Education in Ethiopia}}
[[File:Addis_Abeba_University_(Sam_Effron).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Addis_Abeba_University_(Sam_Effron).jpg|thumb|Entrance of [[:en:Addis_Ababa_University|Addis Ababa University]]]]
Education in Ethiopia was dominated by the Tewahedo Church for many centuries until secular education was adopted in the early 1900s. The current system follows school expansion schemes which are very similar to the system in the rural areas during the 1980s, with an addition of deeper regionalization, providing rural education in students' own languages starting at the elementary level, and with more budget finances allocated to the education sector. The sequence of general education in Ethiopia is six years of primary school, four years of lower secondary school and two years of higher secondary school.<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Teferra|first1=Damtew|last2=Altbach|first2=Philip G.|title=African Higher Education: An International Reference Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/?id=RROdAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=978-0-253-34186-0|pages=316–25}}</ref>

Access to education in Ethiopia has improved significantly. Approximately three million people were in primary school in 1994/95, and by 2008/09, primary enrolment had risen to 15.5&nbsp;million – an increase of over 500%.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Engel|first1=Jakob|title=Ethiopia's progress in education: A rapid and equitablension of access – Summary|url=http://www.developmentprogress.org/sites/developmentprogress.org/files/case-study-summary/ethiopia_web_master_final_summary.pdf|website=Development Progress|publisher=Overseas Development Institute|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In 2013/14, the country had witnessed significant boost in gross enrolment across all regions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://planipolis.iiep.unesco.org/en/search/site?f[0]=im_field_countries%3A1076|title=Search Result: Ethiopia's plans and policies|last=IIEP-UNESCO|date=2017|website=Planipolis|access-date=}}</ref> The national GER was 104.8% for boys, 97.8% for girls and 101.3% across both sexes.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0023/002317/231724e.pdf|title=National EFA review, 2015|last=UNESCO|publisher=UNESCO|year=2015|page=8}}</ref>

The literacy rate has increased in recent years: according to the 1994 census, the literacy rate in Ethiopia was 23.4%.<ref name="Ethnologue" /> In 2007 it was estimated to be 39% (male 49.1% and female 28.9%).<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2103.html "Literacy"] in ''The World Factbook''. ''cia.gov''.</ref> A report by UNDP in 2011 showed that the literacy rate in Ethiopia was 46.7%. The same report also indicated that the female literacy rate has increased from 27 to 39 percent from 2004 to 2011, and the male literacy rate has increased from 49 to 59 percent over the same period for persons 10 years and older.<ref>{{Cite web|title=National Human Development Report 2015 Ethiopia {{!}} Human Development Reports|url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/national-human-development-report-2015-ethiopia|website=hdr.undp.org|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> By 2015, the literacy rate had further increased, to 49.1% (57.2% male and 41.1% female).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.uis.unesco.org/Index.aspx?DataSetCode=EDULIT_DS&popupcustomise=true&lang=en#|title=Education|last=UIS|website=data.uis.unesco.org}}</ref>

== Culture ==
{{Main|Culture of Ethiopia}}
[[File:HagerFikirTheatre.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:HagerFikirTheatre.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Hager_Fikir_Theatre|Hager Fikir Theatre]] in [[:en:Addis_Ababa|Addis Ababa]], founded 1935]]

=== Naming ===
{{Main|Naming conventions in Ethiopia and Eritrea}}Ethiopians have a different naming system to the [[:en:Family_name|family name]]-based Western system. Children add the [[:en:Given_name|given names]] of their father and paternal grandfather consecutively to their own given name. For compatibility purposes, as is done in passports, the grandfather's given name is taken as a family [[:en:Surname|surname]], and a person's given name and their father's given name form the first names.

Everyone is addressed by their given name. In official situations, the prefixes ''Ato'' ('''አቶ''') is used for men; ''Weyzero'' ('''ወይዘሮ''') for married women; and ''Weyzerīt'' ('''ወይዘሪት''') for unmarried women.

=== Calendar ===
{{Main|Ethiopian calendar|Oromo calendar}}
[[File:Celebrate_The_Return_of_Axum_Obelisk_(Detail)_(3172365788).jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Celebrate_The_Return_of_Axum_Obelisk_(Detail)_(3172365788).jpg|thumb|Model commemorating the [[:en:Obelisk_of_Axum|Obelisk of Aksum]]'s return to Ethiopia from Italy, showing the date of its departure and return according to the [[:en:Ethiopian_calendar|Ethiopian calendar]]]]
Ethiopia has several local calendars. The most widely known is the [[:en:Ethiopian_calendar|Ethiopian calendar]], also known as the Ge'ez calendar. It is based on the older Alexandrian or [[:en:Coptic_calendar|Coptic calendar]], which in turn derives from the [[:en:Egyptian_calendar|Egyptian calendar]]. Like the Coptic calendar, the Ethiopian calendar has twelve months of exactly 30 days each plus five or six [[:en:Epagomenal|epagomenal]] days, which comprise a thirteenth month. The Ethiopian months begin on the same days as those of the Coptic calendar, but their names are in Ge'ez.

Like the [[:en:Julian_calendar|Julian calendar]], the sixth epagomenal day—which in essence is a [[:en:Leap_day|leap day]]—is added every four years without exception on 29 August of the Julian calendar, six months before the Julian leap day. Thus, the first day of the Ethiopian year, 1{{nbsp}}Mäskäräm, for years between 1901 and 2099 (inclusive), is usually 11 September ([[:en:Gregorian_calendar|Gregorian]]), but falls on 12 September in years before the Gregorian leap year. Also, a seven- to eight-year gap between the Ethiopian and Gregorian calendars results from an alternate calculation in determining the date of the [[:en:Annunciation|Annunciation]] of [[:en:Jesus|Jesus]].

Another calendrical system was developed around 300 BC by the [[:en:Oromo_people|Oromo]]. A lunar-stellar calendar, this [[:en:Oromo_calendar|Oromo calendar]] relies on astronomical observations of the moon in conjunction with seven particular stars or constellations. Oromo months (stars/lunar phases) are Bittottessa (Iangulum), Camsa (Pleiades), Bufa (Aldebarran), Waxabajjii (Belletrix), Obora Gudda (Central Orion-Saiph), Obora Dikka (Sirius), Birra (full moon), Cikawa (gibbous moon), Sadasaa (quarter moon), Abrasa (large crescent), Ammaji (medium crescent), and Gurrandala (small crescent).<ref>{{cite web|first=Lawrence R|last=Doyle|url=http://www.tusker.com/Archaeo/art.currentanthro.htm|title=The Borana Calendar Reinterpreted|work=tusker.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029073246/http://www.tusker.com/Archaeo/art.currentanthro.htm|archivedate=29 October 2008}}</ref>

=== Time ===
[[:en:Time_in_Ethiopia|Time in Ethiopia]] is counted differently from most countries. The Ethiopian day is reckoned as beginning at 06:00 as opposed to 00:00, coinciding with sunrise throughout the year. To convert between the Ethiopian clock and Western clocks, one must add (or subtract) six hours to the Western time. For example, 02:00 local Addis Ababa time is called "8 at night" in Ethiopia, while 20:00 is called "2 in the evening".

=== Cuisine ===
{{Main|Ethiopian cuisine}}{{see also|List of Ethiopian dishes and foods}}
[[File:Alicha_1.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Alicha_1.jpg|thumb|Typical Ethiopian cuisine: ''[[:en:Injera|injera]]'' (pancake-like bread) and several kinds of ''wat'' (stew)]]
The best-known [[:en:Ethiopian_cuisine|Ethiopian cuisine]] consists of various types of thick [[:en:Meat|meat]] [[:en:Stew|stews]], known as ''[[:en:Wat_(food)|wat]]'' in Ethiopian culture, and [[:en:Vegetable|vegetable]] side dishes served atop [[:en:Injera|injera]], a large [[:en:Sourdough|sourdough]] [[:en:Flatbread|flatbread]] made of [[:en:Teff|teff]] flour. This is not eaten with utensils, but instead one uses the injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes. Almost universally in Ethiopia, it is common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people. It is also a common custom to feed others in your group with your own hands—a tradition referred to as "[[:en:Ethiopian_cuisine#Gursha|gursha]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Simpsons Episode Well-Received by Ethiopians On Social Media|url=http://www.tadias.com/12/01/2011/the-simpsons-episode-well-received-by-ethiopians-on-social-media-elsewhere/|publisher=Tadias Magazine|date=1 December 2011}}</ref> Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no [[:en:Pork|pork]] or [[:en:Shellfish|shellfish]] of any kind, as they are forbidden in the [[:en:Ethiopian_Orthodox|Ethiopian Orthodox]] Christian, Islamic and Jewish faiths.

[[:en:Fit-fit#Kitcha_fit-fit|Chechebsa]], [[:en:Marqa|marqa]], [[:en:Chukko|chukko]], [[:en:Michirra|michirra]] and [[:en:Dhanga_(food)|dhanga]] are the most popular dishes from the [[:en:Oromo_people|Oromo]]. [[:en:Kitfo|Kitfo]], which originated among the [[:en:Gurage_people|Gurage]], is one of the country's most popular delicacies. In addition, [[:en:Doro_wot|Doro wot]] (ደሮ ወጥ in [[:en:Amharic|Amharic]]) and [[:en:Tsebehi_derho|Tsebehi derho]] (ጽብሒ ድርሆ in [[:en:Tigrinya_language|Tigrinya]]), are other popular dishes, originating from northwestern Ethiopia.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} [[:en:Tihlo|Tihlo]] (ጥሕሎ)—which is a type of [[:en:Dumpling|dumpling]]—is prepared from roasted barley flour and originated in the [[:en:Tigray_Region|Tigray Region]]. Tihlo is now very popular in [[:en:Amhara_Region|Amhara]] and spreading further south.<ref>{{cite web|title=Culture of the people of Tigrai|url=http://www.tigraionline.com/bahlina.html|publisher=Tigrai Online|accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref>

=== Media ===
{{main|Communications in Ethiopia|Media in Ethiopia}}
[[File:Ethiopian_Television.JPG|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Ethiopian_Television.JPG|thumb|[[:en:ETV_(Ethiopia)|Ethiopian Broadcasting Corporation]] headquarters in Addis Ababa]]
[[:en:ETV_(Ethiopia)|Ethiopian Broadcasting Corporation]] (EBC), formerly known as ETV, is the government-owned national channel. Other television stations in the country include [[:en:Kana_TV|Kana TV]].

The most widely circulated newspapers in Ethiopia are [[:en:Addis_Fortune|Addis Fortune]], [[:en:Capital_Ethiopia|Capital Ethiopia]], [[:en:Ethiopian_Reporter|Ethiopian Reporter]], Addis Zemen{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} (''Amharic'') and [[:en:Ethiopian_Herald|Ethiopian Herald]]{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}.

The sole internet service provider is the national telecommunications firm [[:en:Ethio_telecom|Ethio Telecom]]. A large portion of users in the country access the internet through mobile devices.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/ethiopia-internet-blocked-618806|title=Why has Ethiopia pulled its mobile internet access again?|last=Gaffey|first=Conor|date=1 June 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref> {{as of|2016|July|}}, there are around 4.29&nbsp;million people who have internet access at their home as compared to a quarter of a million users a decade before that.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.internetlivestats.com/internet-users/ethiopia/|title=Ethiopia Internet Users|last=|first=|date=1 July 2016|website=Internet Live Stats|publisher=Internet Live Stats|access-date=}}</ref> The Ethiopian government has at times intentionally shut down internet service in the country or restricted access to certain social media sites during periods of political unrest. In August 2016, following protest and demonstration in the Oromia Region, all access to the internet was shut down for a period of two days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-36940906|title=What is behind Ethiopia's wave of protests?|date=22 August 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, the government shut down access to the internet for mobile users during a period that coincided with the administration of Ethiopia's university entrance examination. Although the reason for the restriction was not confirmed by the government,<ref name=":3" /> the move was similar to a measure taken during the same period in 2016, after a leak of test questions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/07/ethiopia-blocks-social-media-sites-exam-leak-160711183939642.html|title=Ethiopia blocks social media sites over exam leak|date=11 July 2016|website=Al Jazeera|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/ethiopia-blocks-social-media-facebook-twitter-instagram-scandal-479581|title=Ethiopia has shut down social media and here's why|last=Sharkov|first=Damien|date=12 July 2016|work=Newsweek|access-date=14 August 2017}}</ref>

=== Music ===
{{Main|Music of Ethiopia}}
[[File:Mahmoudahmedfeature.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mahmoudahmedfeature.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Mahmoud_Ahmed|Mahmoud Ahmed]], an Ethiopian singer of [[:en:Gurage|Gurage]] ancestry (2005)]]
The [[:en:Music_of_Ethiopia|music of Ethiopia]] is extremely diverse, with each of the country's 80 ethnic groups being associated with unique sounds. Ethiopian music uses a distinct [[:en:Musical_mode|modal system]] that is [[:en:Pentatonic_scale|pentatonic]], with characteristically long intervals between some notes. As with many other aspects of Ethiopian culture and tradition, tastes in music and lyrics are strongly linked with those in neighboring Eritrea, Somalia, Djibouti, and Sudan.<ref name="Abdullahi">{{cite book|last=Abdullahi|first=Mohamed Diriye|title=Culture and Customs of Somalia|year=2001|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-31333-2|page=170|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2Nu918tYMB8C&pg=PA170|quote=Somali music, a unique kind of music that might be mistaken at first for music from nearby countries such as Ethiopia, the Sudan, or even Arabia, can be recognized by its own tunes and styles.}}</ref><ref name="Tekle">{{cite book|last=Tekle|first=Amare|title=Eritrea and Ethiopia: from conflict to cooperation|year=1994|publisher=The Red Sea Press|isbn=978-0-932415-97-4|page=197|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xbQTEF0rd7wC&pg=PA197|quote=Djibouti, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Somalia and Sudan have significant similarities emanating not only from culture, religion, traditions, history and aspirations&nbsp;... They appreciate similar foods and spices, beverages and sweets, fabrics and tapestry, lyrics and music, and jewellery and fragrances.}}</ref> Traditional singing in Ethiopia presents diverse styles of [[:en:Polyphony|polyphony]] ([[:en:Heterophony|heterophony]], [[:en:Drone_(music)|drone]], [[:en:Imitation|imitation]], and [[:en:Counterpoint|counterpoint]]). Traditionally, lyricism in Ethiopian song writing is strongly associated with views of patriotism or national pride, romance, friendship, and a most unique type of memoire known as 'Tizita'.

=== Sport ===
{{Main|Sport in Ethiopia}}
[[File:Addis_Ababa_Stadium.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Addis_Ababa_Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[:en:Addis_Ababa_Stadium|Addis Ababa Stadium]], built by Italian settlers in 1940]]
The main sports in Ethiopia are [[:en:Track_and_field|track and field]] (particularly [[:en:Long_distance_running|long distance running]]) and [[:en:Association_football|football]]. Ethiopian athletes have won many Olympic gold medals in track and field, most of them in long distance running.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ethiopian Olympic Committee|url=http://www.olympic.org/ethiopia|publisher=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref> Abebe Bikila became the first athlete from a sub Saharan country to win an Olympic Gold medal when he won the Marathon at the 1960 Rome Olympic Games in a world record time of 2:15:16.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/gallery/2012/apr/25/athletics-olympics-2012|title=50 stunning Olympic moments: Abebe Bikila's 1960 marathon victory – in pictures|last=Bloor|first=Steven|date=2012-04-25|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.olympic.org/news/barefooted-bikila-steps-in-for-heroic-marathon-triumph|title=Athletics - Abebe Bikila (ETH)|date=2019-10-13|website=International Olympic Committee|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>

[[:en:Haile_Gebrselassie|Haile Gebrselassie]] is a world-renowned long distance runner with several [[:en:World_record|world records]] under his belt. [[:en:Kenenisa_Bekele|Kenenisa Bekele]] and [[:en:Tirunesh_Dibaba|Tirunesh Dibaba]] are also dominant runners, particularly in the 5,000 and 10,000 meters in which they hold the world records.

Other notable Ethiopian athletes are [[:en:Mamo_Wolde|Mamo Wolde]], [[:en:Miruts_Yifter|Miruts Yifter]], [[:en:Derartu_Tulu|Derartu Tulu]], [[:en:Meseret_Defar|Meseret Defar]], [[:en:Almaz_Ayana|Almaz Ayana]], [[:en:Birhane_Adere|Birhane Adere]], [[:en:Tiki_Gelana|Tiki Gelana]], [[:en:Genzebe_Dibaba|Genzebe Dibaba]], [[:en:Tariku_Bekele|Tariku Bekele]], and [[:en:Gelete_Burka|Gelete Burka]]. {{As of|2012}} and going into 2013, the current national [[:en:Ethiopia_national_football_team|Ethiopian national football team]] (nicknamed the Walayia Antelopes) made history by qualifying for the [[:en:2012_Africa_Cup_of_Nations|2012 Africa Cup of Nations]] and reached the last 10 African football teams in the last stage of [[:en:2014_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_(CAF)|qualification for the 2014 FIFA World Cup]]. Noted players include captain [[:en:Adane_Girma|Adane Girma]] and top scorer [[:en:Saladin_Said|Saladin Said]].

Ethiopia has sub-Saharan Africa's longest [[:en:Basketball|basketball]] tradition as it established a [[:en:Ethiopia_national_basketball_team|national basketball team]] in 1949.{{clear}}

